{"title_page": "Peter J. Otey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name=Peter J. Otey\n| image name=Peter J. Otey.jpeg\n| state=[[Virginia]]\n| district=[[Virginia's 6th congressional district|6th]]\n| party=[[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n| term_start=March 4, 1895\n| term_end=May 4, 1902\n| preceded=[[Paul C. Edmunds]]\n| succeeded=[[Carter Glass]]\n| birth_date={{birth date|1840|12|22}}\n| birth_place=[[Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1902|05|04|1840|12|22}}\n| death_place=Lynchburg, Virginia\n| religion=Presbyterian\n| occupation= Businessman\n| residence= \n| alma_mater= [[Virginia Military Institute]]\n|allegiance = Confederate States of America\n|branch = {{army|CSA}}\n|rank = [[File:Confederate States of America Major.png|15px]] [[Major (rank)|Major]]\n|unit = [[51st Virginia Infantry]]\n|commands = [[30th Virginia Sharpshooters Battalion]]\n|serviceyears = 1861\u20131865\n|battles=[[Battle of Fort Donelson]], [[Battle of Shiloh]], [[Battle of Cedar Creek]], [[Battle of New Market]], [[Battle of Waynesboro, Virginia|Battle of Waynesboro]]\n}}\n'''Peter Johnston Otey''' (December 22, 1840 \u2013 May 4, 1902) was former [[Confederate States Army]] officer and later prisoner of war during the [[American Civil War]], who became businessman, land developer and railroad executive before retiring and winning election to the [[United States House of Representatives]] as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] from [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] and serving three terms before his death.<ref>Virginia Biographical Encyclopedia (online at ancestry.com)</ref><ref>{{CongBio|O000126|name=OTEY, Peter Johnston|inline=1}}</ref>\n\n==Early and family life==\nPeter J. Otey was born on December 22, 1840 in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] to Lucy (n\u00e9e Norvell) and banker [[Mathews family|John Mathews Otey]] (1792\u20131859). He was a nephew of Episcopal Bishop [[James Hervey Otey]], and his ancestors John Floyd (a privateer) and John Otey (commanding Kent County riflemen) fought in the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>DAR Lineage Book Vol. 6, p. 5404</ref> He had at least three elder brothers: Col. Kirkwood Otey (1832\u20131897), Capt. George Gaston Otey (1834\u20131862) and Capt. Water Hays Otey (1837\u20131890). His father owned seven enslaved females and five enslaved males (including 20 and 30 year old black men) in 1850.<ref>1850 U.S.Federal Census Slave schedule for Lynchburg, Campbell county, Virginia</ref> Otey attended private schools in Lynchburg, then like his brothers the [[Virginia Military Institute]]. Shortly before graduating, he and his fellow cadets were sent to combat [[John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry]]. He graduated on July 1, 1860 with a degree in civil engineering.<ref name=mem>Memorial addresses on the life and character of Peter J. Otey (late a representative from Virginia), delivered in the House of Representatives and Senate, Fifty-seventh Congress, first session (1902). Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/memoriale00unit April 23, 2014.</ref>\n\nOtey married Mary Malvina Floyd (1844\u20131915) on April 14, 1863 in [[Wytheville, Virginia]]. Their son John Floyd Otey (1872\u20131888) died as a teenager, although three daughters survived their parents: Mary Warren Otey Mitchell (1866\u20131946; who would become a charter member of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]]), Nannie Louis Otey Miller (1869\u20131935) and Nathalie Floyd Otey Ward (1876\u20131949).<ref>findagrave.vom no. 6862585</ref>\n\n==Confederate service==\nOn the outbreak of the American Civil War, Otey left his job on the Virginia and Kentucky Railroad, and supposedly fired a cannon at Sewell's Point after Virginia seceded and actually hit a Union vessel,<ref>Mem. p. 12</ref> as well as fought with the U.S. Monticello on May 19, 1861.<ref>Michael West, 30th Battalion Virginia Sharpshooters (Virginia Regimental History Series 1995) p. 288</ref> He became a lieutenant in Company S, [[51st Virginia Infantry]] in the [[Army of the Kanawha]] under Col. Gabriel C. Wharton (VMI class of 1847, who had become a civil engineer in Arizona), former VMI mathematics professor Lt.Col. James W. Massie and former Virginia Governor General [[John B. Floyd]] (uncle of his fiancee, later wife). Otey served as a staff officer, and the 51st Virginia was tasked with protecting the [[Kanawha Valley]] and its salt and other mines, but had little success. The regiment suffered defeats at Carnifax Ferry and Cotton Hill in 1861 and in February 1862 at [[Fort Donelson]], [[Tennessee]], although only 2 members surrendered and the majority including this Otey escaped to defend [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].<ref>James A. Davis, 51st Virginia Infantry (Virginia Regimental History Series) pp. 2\u201310</ref> His three elder brothers also became Confederate officers: [[Kirkwood Otey]] commanded the [[11th Virginia Infantry]] including at the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] (during which he sustained a shoulder wound); George Gaston Otey (who had begun the war as adjutant of the [[1st Virginia Infantry]]) organized the \"Otey Company\" of light artillery in March 1862 which was sent to Western Virginia and east Tennessee and became the [[13th Virginia Light Artillery]] by the war's end (after G.G. Otey died in October of wounds received at the [[Battle of Lewisburg]]<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/1371</ref> in what became West Virginia in May); Walter Hays Otey of VMI's class of 1859 served with the 16th Virginia and 56th Virginia before resigning for health reasons and organizing a company of local defense light artillery at the Danville Arsenal.<ref>VMI Historical Rosters Database ID 961</ref>\n\nOn October 5, 1862, Peter Otey was promoted to major of the [[30th Virginia Sharpshooters Battalion]] in [[Robert E. Lee|General Lee]]'s [[Army of Northern Virginia]].<ref>Davis p. 81</ref> He then he fought numerous battles (including the [[Battle of Shiloh]]) and defended Lynchburg as the unit was assigned to General Jubal Early's Army of the Valley. Major Otey receive an arm injury at the [[Battle of Newmarket]], and was sent to Lynchburg to recover. Among those who surrendered after the [[Battle of Waynesboro, Virginia|Battle of Waynesboro]], Major Otey was taken as a [[prisoner of war]] to [[Fort Delaware]], where he remained until the war's end, alongside future House speaker [[Charles F. Crisp]].<ref>mem. p. 11</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter the war, Otey started working as a cashier for the Lynchburg National Bank, sold insurance and was later named the general manager of the Rivermont Land Co.<ref>http://www.retroweb.com/lynchburg/articles/1891_01_08_DV_Lynchburg&Durham.html</ref> Otey worked with for former Confederate General [[William Mahone]] on the [[Atlantic, Mississippi and Ohio Railroad]], but after that bankruptcy, split with that controversial figure. Starting in 1887<ref>[http://spec.lib.vt.edu/railroad/guiderr.htm Railroad Guide: Special Collections, University Libraries, Virginia Tech<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Otry organized and built the [[Lynchburg & Durham Railroad]] and became its president until June 21, 1891, when Otey retired shortly before his railroad merged with the [[Norfolk and Western Railway]].<ref>https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/06/21/103315498.pdf\n</ref>\n\nFirst running for public office in 1894, Otey was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the Fifty-fourth and three succeeding Congresses, serving from March 4, 1895, until his death. He was a delegate to the Democratic National Convention in 1896. On February 1, 1900 Otey introduced H.R. 277, which proposed to purchase land in [[Manassas, Virginia]] to establish a national battle park on the grounds of the [[First Battle of Manassas]], which was implemented (and expended) three decades later during the Great Depression.<ref>Joan Zenzen, Battling for Manassas: The Fifty-Year Preservation Struggle at Manassas (Pennsylvania State University Press 2010) p. 20</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n\nOtey died in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], May 4, 1902, survived by his wife and daughters and was interred in the city's Presbyterian Cemetery.\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n*'''1894'''; Otey was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives with 47.14% of the vote, defeating Republican [[J. Hampton Hoge]] and Independents O.C. Rucker and Frank Smith.\n*'''1896'''; Otey was re-elected with 57% of the vote, defeating NtD (?) DuVal Radford, Republican J. Hampton Hoge, and Populist Joseph Johnston.\n*'''1898'''; Otey was re-elected 66.93% of the vote, defeating Republicans Daniel Butler and Charles A. Heermans and Independents Ira W. Kimmell and D.G. Revere.\n*'''1900'''; Otey was re-elected with 77.54% of the vote, defeating Republican J.B. Stovall, Jr. and Populist A.E. Fairweather.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1900\u201349)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Peter Johnston Otey}}\n* [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uva.x004873426;view=1up;seq=11 Memorial addresses on the life and character of Peter J. Otey, late a representative from Virginia delivered in the House of Representatives and Senate frontispiece 1902]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=6\n| before=[[Paul C. Edmunds]]\n| after=[[Carter Glass]]\n| years=1895\u20131902}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives06}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otey, Peter Johnston}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1902 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army officers]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name=Peter J. Otey\n| image name=Peter J. Otey.jpeg\n| state=[[Virginia]]\n| district=[[Virginia's 6th congressional district|6th]]\n| party=[[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n| term_start=March 4, 1895\n| term_end=May 4, 1902\n| preceded=[[Paul C. Edmunds]]\n| succeeded=[[Carter Glass]]\n| birth_date={{birth date|1840|12|22}}\n| birth_place=[[Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1902|05|04|1840|12|22}}\n| death_place=Lynchburg, Virginia\n| religion=Presbyterian\n| occupation= Businessman\n| residence= \n| alma_mater= [[Virginia Military Institute]]\n|allegiance = Confederate States of America\n|branch = {{army|CSA}}\n|rank = [[File:Confederate States of America Major.png|15px]] [[Major (rank)|Major]]\n|unit = [[51st Virginia Infantry]]\n|commands = [[30th Virginia Sharpshooters Battalion]]\n|serviceyears = 1861\u20131865\n|battles=[[Battle of Fort Donelson]], [[Battle of Shiloh]], [[Battle of Cedar Creek]], [[Battle of New Market]], [[Battle of Waynesboro, Virginia|Battle of Waynesboro]]\n}}\n'''Peter Johnston Otey''' (December 22, 1840 \u2013 May 4, 1902) was former [[Confederate States Army]] officer and later prisoner of war during the [[American Civil War]], who became businessman, land developer and railroad executive before retiring and winning election to the [[United States House of Representatives]] as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] from [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] and serving three terms before his death.<ref>Virginia Biographical Encyclopedia (online at ancestry.com)</ref><ref>{{CongBio|O000126|name=OTEY, Peter Johnston|inline=1}}</ref>\n\n==Early and family life==\nPeter J. Otey was born on December 22, 1840 in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] to Lucy (n\u00e9e Norvell) and banker [[Mathews family (Virginia)|John Mathews Otey]] (1792\u20131859). He was a nephew of Episcopal Bishop [[James Hervey Otey]], and his ancestors John Floyd (a privateer) and John Otey (commanding Kent County riflemen) fought in the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>DAR Lineage Book Vol. 6, p. 5404</ref> He had at least three elder brothers: Col. Kirkwood Otey (1832\u20131897), Capt. George Gaston Otey (1834\u20131862) and Capt. Water Hays Otey (1837\u20131890). His father owned seven enslaved females and five enslaved males (including 20 and 30 year old black men) in 1850.<ref>1850 U.S.Federal Census Slave schedule for Lynchburg, Campbell county, Virginia</ref> Otey attended private schools in Lynchburg, then like his brothers the [[Virginia Military Institute]]. Shortly before graduating, he and his fellow cadets were sent to combat [[John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry]]. He graduated on July 1, 1860 with a degree in civil engineering.<ref name=mem>Memorial addresses on the life and character of Peter J. Otey (late a representative from Virginia), delivered in the House of Representatives and Senate, Fifty-seventh Congress, first session (1902). Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/memoriale00unit April 23, 2014.</ref>\n\nOtey married Mary Malvina Floyd (1844\u20131915) on April 14, 1863 in [[Wytheville, Virginia]]. Their son John Floyd Otey (1872\u20131888) died as a teenager, although three daughters survived their parents: Mary Warren Otey Mitchell (1866\u20131946; who would become a charter member of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]]), Nannie Louis Otey Miller (1869\u20131935) and Nathalie Floyd Otey Ward (1876\u20131949).<ref>findagrave.vom no. 6862585</ref>\n\n==Confederate service==\nOn the outbreak of the American Civil War, Otey left his job on the Virginia and Kentucky Railroad, and supposedly fired a cannon at Sewell's Point after Virginia seceded and actually hit a Union vessel,<ref>Mem. p. 12</ref> as well as fought with the U.S. Monticello on May 19, 1861.<ref>Michael West, 30th Battalion Virginia Sharpshooters (Virginia Regimental History Series 1995) p. 288</ref> He became a lieutenant in Company S, [[51st Virginia Infantry]] in the [[Army of the Kanawha]] under Col. Gabriel C. Wharton (VMI class of 1847, who had become a civil engineer in Arizona), former VMI mathematics professor Lt.Col. James W. Massie and former Virginia Governor General [[John B. Floyd]] (uncle of his fiancee, later wife). Otey served as a staff officer, and the 51st Virginia was tasked with protecting the [[Kanawha Valley]] and its salt and other mines, but had little success. The regiment suffered defeats at Carnifax Ferry and Cotton Hill in 1861 and in February 1862 at [[Fort Donelson]], [[Tennessee]], although only 2 members surrendered and the majority including this Otey escaped to defend [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].<ref>James A. Davis, 51st Virginia Infantry (Virginia Regimental History Series) pp. 2\u201310</ref> His three elder brothers also became Confederate officers: [[Kirkwood Otey]] commanded the [[11th Virginia Infantry]] including at the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] (during which he sustained a shoulder wound); George Gaston Otey (who had begun the war as adjutant of the [[1st Virginia Infantry]]) organized the \"Otey Company\" of light artillery in March 1862 which was sent to Western Virginia and east Tennessee and became the [[13th Virginia Light Artillery]] by the war's end (after G.G. Otey died in October of wounds received at the [[Battle of Lewisburg]]<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/1371</ref> in what became West Virginia in May); Walter Hays Otey of VMI's class of 1859 served with the 16th Virginia and 56th Virginia before resigning for health reasons and organizing a company of local defense light artillery at the Danville Arsenal.<ref>VMI Historical Rosters Database ID 961</ref>\n\nOn October 5, 1862, Peter Otey was promoted to major of the [[30th Virginia Sharpshooters Battalion]] in [[Robert E. Lee|General Lee]]'s [[Army of Northern Virginia]].<ref>Davis p. 81</ref> He then he fought numerous battles (including the [[Battle of Shiloh]]) and defended Lynchburg as the unit was assigned to General Jubal Early's Army of the Valley. Major Otey receive an arm injury at the [[Battle of Newmarket]], and was sent to Lynchburg to recover. Among those who surrendered after the [[Battle of Waynesboro, Virginia|Battle of Waynesboro]], Major Otey was taken as a [[prisoner of war]] to [[Fort Delaware]], where he remained until the war's end, alongside future House speaker [[Charles F. Crisp]].<ref>mem. p. 11</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter the war, Otey started working as a cashier for the Lynchburg National Bank, sold insurance and was later named the general manager of the Rivermont Land Co.<ref>http://www.retroweb.com/lynchburg/articles/1891_01_08_DV_Lynchburg&Durham.html</ref> Otey worked with for former Confederate General [[William Mahone]] on the [[Atlantic, Mississippi and Ohio Railroad]], but after that bankruptcy, split with that controversial figure. Starting in 1887<ref>[http://spec.lib.vt.edu/railroad/guiderr.htm Railroad Guide: Special Collections, University Libraries, Virginia Tech<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Otry organized and built the [[Lynchburg & Durham Railroad]] and became its president until June 21, 1891, when Otey retired shortly before his railroad merged with the [[Norfolk and Western Railway]].<ref>https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/06/21/103315498.pdf\n</ref>\n\nFirst running for public office in 1894, Otey was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the Fifty-fourth and three succeeding Congresses, serving from March 4, 1895, until his death. He was a delegate to the Democratic National Convention in 1896. On February 1, 1900 Otey introduced H.R. 277, which proposed to purchase land in [[Manassas, Virginia]] to establish a national battle park on the grounds of the [[First Battle of Manassas]], which was implemented (and expended) three decades later during the Great Depression.<ref>Joan Zenzen, Battling for Manassas: The Fifty-Year Preservation Struggle at Manassas (Pennsylvania State University Press 2010) p. 20</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n\nOtey died in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], May 4, 1902, survived by his wife and daughters and was interred in the city's Presbyterian Cemetery.\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n*'''1894'''; Otey was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives with 47.14% of the vote, defeating Republican [[J. Hampton Hoge]] and Independents O.C. Rucker and Frank Smith.\n*'''1896'''; Otey was re-elected with 57% of the vote, defeating NtD (?) DuVal Radford, Republican J. Hampton Hoge, and Populist Joseph Johnston.\n*'''1898'''; Otey was re-elected 66.93% of the vote, defeating Republicans Daniel Butler and Charles A. Heermans and Independents Ira W. Kimmell and D.G. Revere.\n*'''1900'''; Otey was re-elected with 77.54% of the vote, defeating Republican J.B. Stovall, Jr. and Populist A.E. Fairweather.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1900\u201349)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Peter Johnston Otey}}\n* [http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uva.x004873426;view=1up;seq=11 Memorial addresses on the life and character of Peter J. Otey, late a representative from Virginia delivered in the House of Representatives and Senate frontispiece 1902]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=6\n| before=[[Paul C. Edmunds]]\n| after=[[Carter Glass]]\n| years=1895\u20131902}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives06}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otey, Peter Johnston}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1902 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army officers]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Newtack101", "label":