{"title_page": "Springfield Illinois Light Artillery", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name  = Springfield Illinois Light Artillery\n|image      = File:Captain Thomas F. Vaughn.jpg\n|image_size = 240px\n|caption    = Capt. Thomas F. Vaughn commanded the battery. \n|dates      = 21 Aug. 1862 \u2013 30 June 1865\n|country    = {{flag|United States|1861}}\n|allegiance = {{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]<br>{{flag|Illinois}} \n|branch     = [[Union Army]]\n|type       = [[Field artillery in the American Civil War|Field Artillery]]\n|size       = [[Artillery Battery]]\n|equipment  = 6 \u00d7 [[14-pounder James rifle]]s\n|notable_commanders = Thomas F. Vaughn\n|battles      = <small>{{tree list}}\n*[[American Civil War]]\n**[[Battle of Bayou Fourche]] (1863)\n**[[Battle of Prairie D'Ane]] (1864)\n**{{tree list/final branch}}[[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry]] (1864)\n{{tree list/end}}\n}}\nThe '''Springfield Illinois Light Artillery''', also known as '''Vaughn's Independent Illinois Battery''' or '''Battery A, 3rd Illinois Light Artillery''', was an [[artillery battery]] from [[Illinois]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. Organized in August 1862, the unit was first stationed at [[Bolivar, Tennessee]]. In August\u2013September 1863 the battery participated in [[Frederick Steele]]'s expedition to [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], being engaged at [[Battle of Bayou Fourche|Bayou Fourche]]. In spring 1864, the battery took part in the [[Camden Expedition]], fighting at [[Battle of Prairie D'Ane|Prairie D'Ane]] and [[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry|Jenkins' Ferry]]. The unit sat out the remainder of the war in Little Rock before being mustered out of service in June 1865. \n\n==Formation==\nThe Springfield Light Artillery was organized at [[Springfield, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on 21 August 1862.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} Thomas F. Vaughn of [[Providence, Rhode Island]] was appointed [[captain (armed forces)|captain]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=747}} Vaughn previously commanded [[Battery B, 1st Rhode Island Light Artillery]] from 25 August 1861{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=20}} until 1 December 1861 when he resigned his commission.{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=52}} Vaughn led the Rhode Island battery at the [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]] where the unit suffered the loss of one gun and several casualties.{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=37}} The other officers of the Springfield Light Artillery were [[First Lieutenant]]s Edward B. Stillings and Henry D. Colby, both from Springfield, and [[Second Lieutenant]]s Charles W. Thomas of [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]] and Louis D. Rosette of Springfield. Rank and file included [[Sergeant Major]] Louis B. Smith, [[First Sergeant]] Alexander Busby, and [[Quartermaster Sergeant]] William E. Fitzhugh, all of Springfield, five [[sergeant]]s (three from Springfield, two from [[Wenona, Illinois|Wenona]]), 12 [[corporal]]s (six from Wenona, four from Springfield, two from [[Magnolia, Illinois|Magnolia]]), one [[Standard-bearer|guidon]] bearer, one [[bugler]], one [[Wagon master|wagoner]], five [[Armed-forces artificer|artificers]], and 93 [[private (rank)|privates]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|pp=747\u2013749}} \n\nAccording to a July 1863 report, the battery was armed with six [[14-pounder James rifle]]s. At that time, the battery reported having the following 3.80-inch ammunition on hand: 180 Hotchkiss [[canister shot]], 36 Tatham's canister shot, 30 James canister shot, 250 James [[solid shot]], and 451 James [[shell (projectile)|common shell]]. The battery originally included a section (two guns) of [[M1841 12-pounder howitzer]]s, so that it also reported having the following 12-pounder smoothbore ammunition: 72 common shell, 42 [[shrapnel shell|spherical case]], and 50 canister shot. In the ordnance tables, the battery was referred to as Company A, 3rd Illinois Light Artillery, though there were no other companies (B, C, D, etc.) listed under the 3rd regiment.{{sfn|Swain|2015}}\n\n==Organizations==\nThe Springfield Light Artillery remained on duty at [[Camp Butler National Cemetery|Camp Butler]] near Springfield from August until 1 November 1862. The battery traveled to Bolivar, Tennessee on 1\u20138 November where it was attached to the District of [[Jackson, Tennessee]] in the original [[XIII Corps (Union Army)|XIII Corps]], [[Army of the Tennessee]]. From December 1862 to March 1863, Vaughn's Illinois Battery defended the Post of Bolivar, District of Jackson, [[XVI Corps (Union Army)|XVI Corps]]. In March\u2013May 1863, the battery was part of the 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, XVI Corps. In May\u2013August 1863, it transferred to the 3rd Brigade, 3rd Division, XVI Corps. Vaughn's Battery was assigned to True's Brigade, Arkansas Expedition in September 1863. The battery was part of Artillery, 2nd Division, [[Army of Arkansas]] from September 1863 to January 1864. The unit formed part of Artillery, 2nd Division, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], Department of Arkansas in January\u2013March 1864. The Springfield Light Artillery was in the 2nd Brigade, 1st Division, VII Corps in March\u2013April 1864. The unit was reassigned to Artillery, 3rd Division, VII Corps in April\u2013May 1864. Vaughn's Battery was part of Artillery, 1st Division, VII Corps from May 1864 to June 1865.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Frederick Steele cropped.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.7|alt=Black and white photo shows a man with a foot-long beard. He wears a dark, double breasted uniform with general's stars on the shoulder tabs.|Frederick Steele]]\n\nThe Springfield Illinois Light Artillery arrived at Bolivar and was assigned to a brigade commanded by [[Mason Brayman]]. On 15\u201320 December 1862, two sections participated in an expedition against Confederate raiders under [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=751}} Vaughn's Battery performed garrison duty at Bolivar from November 1862 until 18 June 1863. The battery was parceled out to guard the [[Memphis and Charleston Railroad]] with one section each at [[Moscow, Tennessee|Moscow]], [[Collierville, Tennessee|Collierville]], and [[Germantown, Tennessee|Germantown]] through 23 August 1863. The unit traveled to [[Helena, Arkansas]] on 24 August\u20132 September 1863, then joined [[Frederick Steele]]'s expedition to Little Rock on 2\u201310 September 1863.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} \n\nIn the expedition's order of battle, Colonel James M. True's Independent Brigade included the notation, \"Ill. Battery, Capt. Thomas F. Vaughan\".{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987a|p=461}} On 5 August 1863, Steele began his campaign by marching from Helena to the [[White River (Arkansas\u2013Missouri)|White River]] with two infantry divisions and one cavalry brigade. Steele met [[John Davidson (general)|John Davidson's]] 6,000 Union cavalry and the combined 13,000-man force advanced west from [[DeValls Bluff, Arkansas|DeValls Bluff]] on 18 August. True's brigade joined later and increased Steele's force to 14,500 soldiers, of whom only 10,500 men were present for duty. [[Sterling Price]] entrenched most of his 7,749 Confederate troops on the north bank of the [[Arkansas River]], with a weaker force watching the south bank.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987a|p=457}} \n\nThe Springfield Illinois Light Artillery fought at the [[Battle of Bayou Fourche]] and the subsequent capture of Little Rock on 10 September.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} On the evening of 9 September, Federal engineers began constructing a pontoon bridge at Terry's Ferry on the Arkansas River downstream from Little Rock. The next morning, the bridge was fired on by Confederate artillery, but it was quickly silenced by a converging bombardment by several Union batteries deployed on the north bank. By 10:00 am, Union infantry secured a bridgehead on the south bank and Davidson's cavalry began crossing. Meanwhile, Steele advanced along the north bank with the bulk of his infantry to confront Price's defenses. On the south bank, Davidson's cavalry brigades under [[John Montgomery Glover]] and [[Lewis Merrill]] moved west to Bayou Fourche where [[John S. Marmaduke]] organized a defensive position. Supported by artillery firing from the north bank of the Arkansas River, Glover's brigade turned the Confederate left flank. When Price saw that his north bank defenses were outflanked by the Union advance along the south bank, he ordered Little Rock to be evacuated.{{sfn|Christ|2017}} \n\nVaughn's Battery performed garrison duty at Little Rock from September 1863 until March 1864. One section was sent to defend [[Lewisburg, Arkansas]] between 19 October 1863 and 15 March 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} First Lieutenant Stillings resigned on 18 February 1864 and Second Lieutenant Thomas was promoted to fill the vacancy. Another 72 men were recruited into the battery, most of them in December 1863 and January 1864, but several joined the unit in 1865. The wagoner, one sergeant, and one private drowned in the Arkansas River at Little Rock. Others died or deserted. One private was sentenced to [[Alton Military Prison]] on 2 May 1863 to serve out his term of enlistment.{{sfn|Reece|1901|pp=747\u2013749}}      \n\n[[File:Etc 450.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|alt=Color photo shows a domed building.|[[Old State Capitol State Historic Site]] preserves the Civil War era Springfield, Illinois capitol.]]\n\nOn 17 March 1864, the Springfield Illinois Light Artillery was reunited and participated in Steele's [[Camden Expedition]]{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=751}} from 23 March\u20133 May 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} During the campaign, Vaughn's Battery was part of the artillery contingent of [[Frederick C. Salomon]]'s 3rd Division. Steele's effective force numbered 13,000 troops of which about 2,500 became casualties.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987b|p=368}} There was a skirmish at [[Okolona, Arkansas|Okolona]] on 2\u20133 April. The [[Battle of Prairie D'Ane]] occurred on 9\u201312 April.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} Steele's VII Corps seized [[Camden, Arkansas|Camden]] but was unable to maintain its position because Confederate cavalry wrecked two supply convoys at [[Battle of Poison Spring|Poison Spring]] and [[Battle of Marks' Mills|Marks' Mills]]. On 26 April, Steele's force abandoned Camden and marched back toward Little Rock. The Federal column reached  the [[Saline River (Ouachita River tributary)|Saline River]] on 29 April and paused while the engineers built a pontoon bridge across the rain-swollen stream. The [[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry]] was fought on 30 April. Though outnumbered, Salomon's soldiers improvised defensive positions on the south bank and repulsed repeated Confederate assaults during the morning. After the last attack ended at 12:30 pm, Salomon's division withdrew across the river and destroyed the pontoon bridge. The Federals reported 63 killed, 413 wounded, and 45 missing, while Confederate returns showed 86 killed, 356 wounded, and one missing. Steele's force continued its retreat to Little Rock.{{sfn|Clements|2017}}  \n\nVaughn's Battery was on garrison duty at Little Rock from May 1864 to June 1865.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} First Lieutenant Colby resigned on 28 June 1864 and Second Lieutenants Rosette and John Schaefer of Wenona were promoted to first lieutenant. Second Lieutenant James Irwin of [[Chatham, Illinois|Chatham]] was promoted to first lieutenant on 19 July 1864. First Lieutenant Thomas resigned on 17 September 1864. The other new second lieutenants were Ward Bertram and Albert Flood of Springfield and William M. Gillmore of Wenona.{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=747}} The battery was ordered to Springfield, Illinois on 25 June and mustered out 30 June 1865. During its service one enlisted man was killed in battle and 22 enlisted men died by disease.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Illinois Civil War units]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Battles & Leaders|1987a}} |title=Battles and Leaders of the Civil War |volume=3 |year=1987a |orig-year=1883 |publisher=Castle |location=Secaucus, N.J. |isbn=0-89009-571-X }}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Battles & Leaders|1987b}} |title=Battles and Leaders of the Civil War |volume=4 |year=1987b |orig-year=1883 |publisher=Castle |location=Secaucus, N.J. |isbn=0-89009-572-8 }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Christ |first=Mark K. |title=Engagement at Bayou Fourche |year=2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of Arkansas |location=Little Rock, Ark. |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/entries/engagement-at-bayou-fourche-519/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Clements |first=Derek Allen |title=Engagement at Jenkins' Ferry |year=2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of Arkansas |location=Little Rock, Ark. |access-date=April 11, 2020 |url=https://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/entries/engagement-at-jenkins-ferry-1136/ }}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Dyer |first=Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion |year=1908 |location=Des Moines, Iowa |publisher=Dyer Publishing Co. }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Reece |first=J. N. |title=Report of the Adjutant General of the State of Illinois: 1861-1866 |year=1901 |location=Springfield, Ill. |publisher=Journal Company, Printers and Binders |volume=8 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/reportofadjutant08illi1/page/750/mode/2up }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Rhodes |first=John H. |title=The History of Battery B, First Regiment Rhode Island Light Artillery |year=1894 |location=Providence, R.I. |publisher=Snow & Farnham Printers |access-date=April 12, 2020 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mmgtAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&#v=onepage&q&f=false }} \n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, December 31 1862, Independent Illinois Batteries and \"Others\" |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2015 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/tag/vaughns-independent-illinois-battery/ }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Dyer |first=Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion: Springfield Independent Battery Light Artillery \"Vaughan's\" |year=2016 |orig-year=1908 |publisher=Civil War Archive |url=http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unilart2.htm#vaughans}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Illinois Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Artillery units and formations of the American Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name  = Springfield Illinois Light Artillery\n|image      = File:Captain Thomas F. Vaughn.jpg\n|image_size = 240px\n|caption    = Capt. Thomas F. Vaughn commanded the battery. \n|dates      = 21 Aug. 1862 \u2013 30 June 1865\n|country    = {{flag|United States|1861}}\n|allegiance = {{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]<br>{{flag|Illinois}} \n|branch     = [[Union Army]]\n|type       = [[Field artillery in the American Civil War|Field Artillery]]\n|size       = [[Artillery Battery]]\n|equipment  = 6 \u00d7 [[14-pounder James rifle]]s\n|notable_commanders = Thomas F. Vaughn\n|battles      = <small>{{tree list}}\n*[[American Civil War]]\n**[[Battle of Bayou Fourche]] (1863)\n**[[Battle of Prairie D'Ane]] (1864)\n**{{tree list/final branch}}[[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry]] (1864)\n{{tree list/end}}\n}}\nThe '''Springfield Illinois Light Artillery''', also known as '''Vaughn's Independent Illinois Battery''' or '''Battery A, 3rd Illinois Light Artillery''', was an [[artillery battery]] from [[Illinois]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. Organized in August 1862, the unit was first stationed at [[Bolivar, Tennessee]]. In August\u2013September 1863 the battery participated in [[Frederick Steele]]'s expedition to [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], being engaged at [[Battle of Bayou Fourche|Bayou Fourche]]. In spring 1864, the battery took part in the [[Camden Expedition]], fighting at [[Battle of Prairie D'Ane|Prairie D'Ane]] and [[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry|Jenkins' Ferry]]. The unit sat out the remainder of the war in Little Rock before being mustered out of service in June 1865. \n\n==Formation==\nThe Springfield Light Artillery was organized at [[Springfield, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on 21 August 1862.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} Thomas F. Vaughn of [[Providence, Rhode Island]] was appointed [[captain (armed forces)|captain]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=747}} Vaughn previously commanded [[Battery B, 1st Rhode Island Light Artillery]] from 25 August 1861{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=20}} until 1 December 1861 when he resigned his commission.{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=52}} Vaughn led the Rhode Island battery at the [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]] where the unit suffered the loss of one gun and several casualties.{{sfn|Rhodes|1894|p=37}} The other officers of the Springfield Light Artillery were [[First Lieutenant]]s Edward B. Stillings and Henry D. Colby, both from Springfield, and [[Second Lieutenant]]s Charles W. Thomas of [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]] and Louis D. Rosette of Springfield. Rank and file included [[Sergeant Major]] Louis B. Smith, [[First Sergeant]] Alexander Busby, and [[Quartermaster Sergeant]] William E. Fitzhugh, all of Springfield, five [[sergeant]]s (three from Springfield, two from [[Wenona, Illinois|Wenona]]), 12 [[corporal]]s (six from Wenona, four from Springfield, two from [[Magnolia, Illinois|Magnolia]]), one [[Standard-bearer|guidon]] bearer, one [[bugler]], one [[Wagon master|wagoner]], five [[Armed-forces artificer|artificers]], and 93 [[private (rank)|privates]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|pp=747\u2013749}} \n\nAccording to a July 1863 report, the battery was armed with six [[14-pounder James rifle]]s. At that time, the battery reported having the following 3.80-inch ammunition on hand: 180 Hotchkiss [[canister shot]], 36 Tatham's canister shot, 30 James canister shot, 250 James [[solid shot]], and 451 James [[shell (projectile)|common shell]]. The battery originally included a section (two guns) of [[M1841 12-pounder howitzer]]s, so that it also reported having the following 12-pounder smoothbore ammunition: 72 common shell, 42 [[shrapnel shell|spherical case]], and 50 canister shot. In the ordnance tables, the battery was referred to as Company A, 3rd Illinois Light Artillery, though there were no other companies (B, C, D, etc.) listed under the 3rd regiment.{{sfn|Swain|2015}}\n\n==Organizations==\nThe Springfield Light Artillery remained on duty at Camp Butler near Springfield from August until 1 November 1862. The battery traveled to Bolivar, Tennessee on 1\u20138 November where it was attached to the District of [[Jackson, Tennessee]] in the original [[XIII Corps (Union Army)|XIII Corps]], [[Army of the Tennessee]]. From December 1862 to March 1863, Vaughn's Illinois Battery defended the Post of Bolivar, District of Jackson, [[XVI Corps (Union Army)|XVI Corps]]. In March\u2013May 1863, the battery was part of the 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, XVI Corps. In May\u2013August 1863, it transferred to the 3rd Brigade, 3rd Division, XVI Corps. Vaughn's Battery was assigned to True's Brigade, Arkansas Expedition in September 1863. The battery was part of Artillery, 2nd Division, [[Army of Arkansas]] from September 1863 to January 1864. The unit formed part of Artillery, 2nd Division, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], Department of Arkansas in January\u2013March 1864. The Springfield Light Artillery was in the 2nd Brigade, 1st Division, VII Corps in March\u2013April 1864. The unit was reassigned to Artillery, 3rd Division, VII Corps in April\u2013May 1864. Vaughn's Battery was part of Artillery, 1st Division, VII Corps from May 1864 to June 1865.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Frederick Steele cropped.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.7|alt=Black and white photo shows a man with a foot-long beard. He wears a dark, double breasted uniform with general's stars on the shoulder tabs.|Frederick Steele]]\n\nThe Springfield Illinois Light Artillery arrived at Bolivar and was assigned to a brigade commanded by [[Mason Brayman]]. On 15\u201320 December 1862, two sections participated in an expedition against Confederate raiders under [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]].{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=751}} Vaughn's Battery performed garrison duty at Bolivar from November 1862 until 18 June 1863. The battery was parceled out to guard the [[Memphis and Charleston Railroad]] with one section each at [[Moscow, Tennessee|Moscow]], [[Collierville, Tennessee|Collierville]], and [[Germantown, Tennessee|Germantown]] through 23 August 1863. The unit traveled to [[Helena, Arkansas]] on 24 August\u20132 September 1863, then joined [[Frederick Steele]]'s expedition to Little Rock on 2\u201310 September 1863.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} \n\nIn the expedition's order of battle, Colonel James M. True's Independent Brigade included the notation, \"Ill. Battery, Capt. Thomas F. Vaughan\".{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987a|p=461}} On 5 August 1863, Steele began his campaign by marching from Helena to the [[White River (Arkansas\u2013Missouri)|White River]] with two infantry divisions and one cavalry brigade. Steele met [[John Davidson (general)|John Davidson's]] 6,000 Union cavalry and the combined 13,000-man force advanced west from [[DeValls Bluff, Arkansas|DeValls Bluff]] on 18 August. True's brigade joined later and increased Steele's force to 14,500 soldiers, of whom only 10,500 men were present for duty. [[Sterling Price]] entrenched most of his 7,749 Confederate troops on the north bank of the [[Arkansas River]], with a weaker force watching the south bank.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987a|p=457}} \n\nThe Springfield Illinois Light Artillery fought at the [[Battle of Bayou Fourche]] and the subsequent capture of Little Rock on 10 September.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} On the evening of 9 September, Federal engineers began constructing a pontoon bridge at Terry's Ferry on the Arkansas River downstream from Little Rock. The next morning, the bridge was fired on by Confederate artillery, but it was quickly silenced by a converging bombardment by several Union batteries deployed on the north bank. By 10:00 am, Union infantry secured a bridgehead on the south bank and Davidson's cavalry began crossing. Meanwhile, Steele advanced along the north bank with the bulk of his infantry to confront Price's defenses. On the south bank, Davidson's cavalry brigades under [[John Montgomery Glover]] and [[Lewis Merrill]] moved west to Bayou Fourche where [[John S. Marmaduke]] organized a defensive position. Supported by artillery firing from the north bank of the Arkansas River, Glover's brigade turned the Confederate left flank. When Price saw that his north bank defenses were outflanked by the Union advance along the south bank, he ordered Little Rock to be evacuated.{{sfn|Christ|2017}} \n\nVaughn's Battery performed garrison duty at Little Rock from September 1863 until March 1864. One section was sent to defend [[Lewisburg, Arkansas]] between 19 October 1863 and 15 March 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} First Lieutenant Stillings resigned on 18 February 1864 and Second Lieutenant Thomas was promoted to fill the vacancy. Another 72 men were recruited into the battery, most of them in December 1863 and January 1864, but several joined the unit in 1865. The wagoner, one sergeant, and one private drowned in the Arkansas River at Little Rock. Others died or deserted. One private was sentenced to [[Alton Military Prison]] on 2 May 1863 to serve out his term of enlistment.{{sfn|Reece|1901|pp=747\u2013749}}      \n\n[[File:Etc 450.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|alt=Color photo shows a domed building.|[[Old State Capitol State Historic Site]] preserves the Civil War era Springfield, Illinois capitol.]]\n\nOn 17 March 1864, the Springfield Illinois Light Artillery was reunited and participated in Steele's [[Camden Expedition]]{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=751}} from 23 March\u20133 May 1864.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} During the campaign, Vaughn's Battery was part of the artillery contingent of [[Frederick C. Salomon]]'s 3rd Division. Steele's effective force numbered 13,000 troops of which about 2,500 became casualties.{{sfn|Battles & Leaders|1987b|p=368}} There was a skirmish at [[Okolona, Arkansas|Okolona]] on 2\u20133 April. The [[Battle of Prairie D'Ane]] occurred on 9\u201312 April.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} Steele's VII Corps seized [[Camden, Arkansas|Camden]] but was unable to maintain its position because Confederate cavalry wrecked two supply convoys at [[Battle of Poison Spring|Poison Spring]] and [[Battle of Marks' Mills|Marks' Mills]]. On 26 April, Steele's force abandoned Camden and marched back toward Little Rock. The Federal column reached  the [[Saline River (Ouachita River tributary)|Saline River]] on 29 April and paused while the engineers built a pontoon bridge across the rain-swollen stream. The [[Battle of Jenkins' Ferry]] was fought on 30 April. Though outnumbered, Salomon's soldiers improvised defensive positions on the south bank and repulsed repeated Confederate assaults during the morning. After the last attack ended at 12:30 pm, Salomon's division withdrew across the river and destroyed the pontoon bridge. The Federals reported 63 killed, 413 wounded, and 45 missing, while Confederate returns showed 86 killed, 356 wounded, and one missing. Steele's force continued its retreat to Little Rock.{{sfn|Clements|2017}}  \n\nVaughn's Battery was on garrison duty at Little Rock from May 1864 to June 1865.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}} First Lieutenant Colby resigned on 28 June 1864 and Second Lieutenants Rosette and John Schaefer of Wenona were promoted to first lieutenant. Second Lieutenant James Irwin of [[Chatham, Illinois|Chatham]] was promoted to first lieutenant on 19 July 1864. First Lieutenant Thomas resigned on 17 September 1864. The other new second lieutenants were Ward Bertram and Albert Flood of Springfield and William M. Gillmore of Wenona.{{sfn|Reece|1901|p=747}} The battery was ordered to Springfield, Illinois on 25 June and mustered out 30 June 1865. During its service one enlisted man was killed in battle and 22 enlisted men died by disease.{{sfn|Dyer|1908}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Illinois Civil War units]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Battles & Leaders|1987a}} |title=Battles and Leaders of the Civil War |volume=3 |year=1987a |orig-year=1883 |publisher=Castle |location=Secaucus, N.J. |isbn=0-89009-571-X }}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Battles & Leaders|1987b}} |title=Battles and Leaders of the Civil War |volume=4 |year=1987b |orig-year=1883 |publisher=Castle |location=Secaucus, N.J. |isbn=0-89009-572-8 }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Christ |first=Mark K. |title=Engagement at Bayou Fourche |year=2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of Arkansas |location=Little Rock, Ark. |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/entries/engagement-at-bayou-fourche-519/ }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Clements |first=Derek Allen |title=Engagement at Jenkins' Ferry |year=2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of Arkansas |location=Little Rock, Ark. |access-date=April 11, 2020 |url=https://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/entries/engagement-at-jenkins-ferry-1136/ }}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Dyer |first=Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion |year=1908 |location=Des Moines, Iowa |publisher=Dyer Publishing Co. }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Reece |first=J. N. |title=Report of the Adjutant General of the State of Illinois: 1861-1866 |year=1901 |location=Springfield, Ill. |publisher=Journal Company, Printers and Binders |volume=8 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/reportofadjutant08illi1/page/750/mode/2up }}\n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Rhodes |first=John H. |title=The History of Battery B, First Regiment Rhode Island Light Artillery |year=1894 |location=Providence, R.I. |publisher=Snow & Farnham Printers |access-date=April 12, 2020 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mmgtAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&#v=onepage&q&f=false }} \n*{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Swain |first=Craig |title=Summary Statement, December 31 1862, Independent Illinois Batteries and \"Others\" |publisher=To the Sound of the Guns |year=2015 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://markerhunter.wordpress.com/tag/vaughns-independent-illinois-battery/ }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Dyer |first=Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion: Springfield Independent Battery Light Artillery \"Vaughan's\" |year=2016 |orig-year=1908 |publisher=Civil War Archive |url=http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unilart2.htm#vaughans}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Illinois Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Artillery units and formations of the American Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "Djmaschek", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrganizations:Add Camp Butler link.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Springfield_Illinois_Light_Artillery"}
{"title_page": "Notiomastodon", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = ''Notiomastodon''\n| fossil_range = late [[Early Pleistocene]]-Early [[Holocene]] <br> (Possible Earliest Pleistocene record) <br>~{{Fossil range|0.8|0.011|earliest=2.5}}\n| image = Stegomastodon CCB.JPG\n| image2 = Stegomastodon platensis.JPG\n| image_width = 250px\n| image_caption = Skeleton at the Centro Cultural del Bicentenario de Santiago del Estero\n| image2_caption = Skull at the Natural History Museum, London\n| parent_authority = Cabrera, 1929\n| taxon = Notiomastodon platensis\n| authority = ([[Florentino Ameghino|Ameghino]], 1888) [originally ''Mastodon'']\n| synonyms = * ''Stegomastodon platensis'' <small>Ameghino 1888</small>\n* ''Stegomastodon waringi'' <small>Holland 1920</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon waringi'' <small>Holland 1920</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon chimborazi'' <small>Proa\u00f1o 1922</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon guayasensis'' <small>Hoffstetter 1952</small>\n* ''Amahuacatherium peruvium'' <small>Romero-Pittman 1996</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Notiomastodon''''' is an extinct [[proboscidea]]n genus of [[gomphothere]]s (a distant relative to modern [[elephants]]) endemic to [[South America]] from the [[Pleistocene]] to the [[Holocene]].<ref name=\"ShoshaniTassy2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Shoshani|first1=Jeheskel|last2=Tassy|first2=Pascal|title=Advances in proboscidean taxonomy & classification, anatomy & physiology, and ecology & behavior|journal=Quaternary International|volume=126\u2013128|year=2005|pages=5\u201320|issn=1040-6182|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2004.04.011|bibcode=2005QuInt.126....5S}}</ref> It was among the last known gomphotheres and one of two South American gomphotheres alongside ''[[Cuvieronius]]'' and was the predominant gomphothere on the continent ranging widely over most of South America excluding the [[Andes|High Andes]]. The species has a long and convoluted taxonomic history due to its morphological variability and confusion with related gomphothere taxa, which was only resolved during the 2010's.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n[[File:Gomphothere_Teeth_South_America_Cuvier_1806.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.56|Two gomphothere teeth from Cuvier (1806) with A referring to \u201c''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\u201d and B referring to \u201c''mastodonte humboldien''\u201d]]\nProboscideans in South America were first described by [[Georges Cuvier]] in 1806,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cuvier|first=Georges|title=Sur diff\u00e9rentes dents du genre des mastodontes, mais d'esp\u00e8ces moindres que celle de l'Ohio, trouv\u00e9es en plusieurs lieux des deux continents|journal=Annales du Mus\u00e9um d'Histoire Naturelle|volume=7|pages=401\u2013420|year=1806}}</ref> but he failed to give them specific names beyond \"Mastodon\".  [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim|Fischer]] in 1814 assigned the \u201c''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\u201d specimen the first specific name \"''Mastotherium hyodon''\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=Gotthelf|author-link=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim|title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata in Usum Praelectionem Academiae Imperialis Medico-Chirurgicae Mosquensis Edita: Vol 3. Classium, ordinum, generum illustratione perpetua aucta|trans-title=Illustrated Zoognosia in Synoptic Tables, Produced from Lectures in the Imperial Medico-Surgical Academy of Moscow by the Author, Gotthelf Fischer: Vol. 3, Classes, Orders, Genera, Enlarged Throughout with Illustration|edition=1|volume=3|publisher=Nikolai Sergeyevich Vsevolozhsky|location=Moscow|language=la|date=1813|url=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc}}</ref>{{rp|340}} In 1824, Cuvier classified the fossils of ''\"Mastodon andium\"'' as the \"''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\" specimen, and  ''\"Mastodon humboldtii\"'' to the \"''mastodonte humboldien''\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Georges|last=Cuvier|title=Recherches sur les ossemens fossiles, ou l'on r\u00e9tablit les caract\u00e8res de plusieurs animaux dont les r\u00e9volutions du globe ont d\u00e9truit les esp\u00e8ces|date=1824|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/002004474|publisher=Chez G. Dufour et E. d'Ocagne}}</ref> Due to the [[Principle of Priority]], this meant that ''\"Mastodon andium\"'' was invalid, as \"''Mastotherium hyodon''\" was named first from the same specimen. Today, neither tooth is considered diagnostic to any specific taxon.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> \n\n\n''Notiomastodon'',{{refn|group=\"nb\"|From the {{lang-grc|\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}} ({{transl|grc|n\u00f3tios}}, \"southern\")<ref>{{LSJ|no/tios|\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2|ref}}</ref>}} \"southern mastodon\" was named by Cabrera (1929). It was assigned to the Gomphotheriidae by Carroll (1988).\n\nFor centuries, the taxonomy of gomphotheres, including ''Notiomastodon'' had been subject to debate, with many generic and specific names for similar South American gomphotheres. The species is currently under dispute, whether it should belong to ''Notiomastodon'' or ''[[Stegomastodon]]''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Perea|first=D.|last2=Alberdi|first2=M. T.|date=2015-12-30|title=Los gonfot\u00e9ridos (Mammalia, Proboscidea) de Uruguay: taxonom\u00eda, estratigraf\u00eda y cronolog\u00eda|journal=Estudios Geol\u00f3gicos|volume=71|issue=2|pages=e036|doi=10.3989/egeol.41864.346|issn=1988-3250|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /><ref name=\"Stegomastodon\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo|title=Mythbusting evolutionary issues on South American Gomphotheriidae (Mammalia: Proboscidea)|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|date= 15 February 2015|volume=110|pages=23\u201325|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2014.12.013}}</ref> as regardless of genus, the species is considered [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonymous]] with ''Haplomastodon'' by most authors, as the specimens were not considered morphologically distinct from this species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lucas|first=Spencer G.|last2=Yuan|first2=Wang|last3=Min|first3=Liu|date=2013-01-01|title=The palaeobiogeography of South American gomphotheres|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82348728.pdf|journal=Journal of Palaeogeography|volume=2|issue=1|pages=19\u201340|doi=10.3724/SP.J.1261.2013.00015|doi-broken-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref name=\"Moth\u00e9Avilla2012\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Cozzuol|first3=Mario A.|title=The South American Gomphotheres (Mammalia, Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae): Taxonomy, Phylogeny, and Biogeography|journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution|year=2012|issn=1064-7554|doi=10.1007/s10914-012-9192-3|volume=20|pages=23\u201332}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Cozzuol|first3=M\u00e1rio|last4=Winck|first4=Gisele R.|title=Taxonomic revision of the Quaternary gomphotheres (Mammalia: Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae) from the South American lowlands|journal=Quaternary International|volume=276\u2013277|pages=2\u20137|date= 25 October 2012|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2011.05.018|bibcode=2012QuInt.276....2M}}</ref> This article treats ''Notiomastodon'' separately because in phylogenetic analyses, ''Notiomastodon/Stegomastodon platensis'' specimens are not sister taxa, which would make the genus [[polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /><ref name=\"a\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Ferretti|first=Marco P.|title=Anatomy of Haplomastodon chimborazi (Mammalia, Proboscidea) from the late Pleistocene of Ecuador and its bearing on the phylogeny and systematics of south American gomphotheres|journal=Geodiversitas|volume=32|issue=4|pages=663\u2013721|date=2010|doi=10.5252/g2010n4a3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Ferretti|first2=Marco P.|last3=Avilla|first3=Leonardo S.|date=2017-06-03|title=Running Over the Same Old Ground: Stegomastodon Never Roamed South America|journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution|volume=26|issue=2|pages=165\u2013177|doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9392-y|issn=1064-7554}}</ref> However, some authors think this is inconclusive, as they think the North American ''Stegomastodon'' material is too scarce and fragmentary to make a definitive statement.<ref name=\"Stegomastodon\">{{cite journal|last=Labarca|first=R.|last2=Alberdi|first2=M.T.|last3=Prado|first3=J.L.|last4=Mansilla|first4=P.|last5=Mourgues|first5=F.A.|title=Nuevas evidencias acerca de la presencia de Stegomastodon platensis Ameghino, 1888, Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae, en el Pleistoceno tard\u00edo de Chile central/New evidences on the presence of Stegomastodon platensis Ameghino, 1888, Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae, in the Late Pleistocene of Central Chile|journal=Estudios Geol\u00f3gicos|volume=72|date=18 April 2016|url=http://estudiosgeol.revistas.csic.es/index.php/estudiosgeol/article/view/941/1075}}</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Evolution ==\n''Notiomastodon'' belongs to the family [[Gomphotheriidae]], a group of animals distantly related to modern elephants and [[mammoth]]s. ''Notiomastodon'' seems to have had a 4-million-year-long [[ghost lineage]], diverging from the clade that contains ''[[Rhynchotherium]]'' and ''[[Cuvieronius]]'' around the Late [[Miocene]]. This would imply that ''Notiomastodon'' had been evolving in southern [[Central America]], where the fossils are poorly sampled, prior to its migration into South America during the [[Pliocene]] or Pleistocene.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> Gomphotheres arrived in South America after the formation of the [[Isthmus of Panama]] as part of the [[Great American Interchange|Great American Biotic Interchange]], alongside many other taxa from North America. The oldest known record of gomphotheres in South America is a fragmentary vertebra from the Earliest Pleistocene (~2.5 Ma) [[Uquia Formation]] of Argentina<ref>Cione, A.L., Gasparini, G.M., Soibelzon, E., Soibelzon, L.H., Tonni, E.P., 2015. The Great American Biotic Interchange in Southern South America: Land Mammal Biostratigraphy, Climatic Evolution and Faunal Integration. Springer Briefs in Earth System Sciences. Springer, New York-London</ref> The oldest known remains definitively attributable to ''Notiomastodon'' are known from the late Early Pleistocene (1.2-0.8 ma) from the Rio de la Plata, also in Argentina, consisting of a pair of tusks and other associated remains.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> A 2019 study using [[collagen]] sequencing found ''Notiomastodon'' closer to ''[[Mastodon|Mammut]]'' than to extant elephants, though how this effects gomphothere phylogeny is unclear.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buckley|first=Michael|last2=Recabarren|first2=Omar P.|last3=Lawless|first3=Craig|last4=Garc\u00eda|first4=Nuria|last5=Pino|first5=Mario|date=November 2019|title=A molecular phylogeny of the extinct South American gomphothere through collagen sequence analysis|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=224|pages=105882|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2019.105882|bibcode=2019QSRv..22405882B|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Phylogeny ==\nThe phylogenetic position among trilophodont gomphotheres according to Moth\u00e9 et al., 2016 is:<ref name=a>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Ferretti|first2=Marco P.|last3=Avilla|first3=Leonardo S.|title=The Dance of Tusks: Rediscovery of Lower Incisors in the Pan-American Proboscidean ''Cuvieronius hyodon'' Revises Incisor Evolution in Elephantimorpha|journal=PLOS ONE|date=12 January 2016|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147009|pmid=26756209|pmc=4710528|volume=11|issue=1|page=e0147009|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147009M}}</ref>\n\n{{clade\n   |label1={{extinct}}[[Gomphotheriidae]] (Gomphotheres)\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{extinct}}''[[Gomphotherium]]''\n      |label2=\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{extinct}}''[[Gnathabelodon]]''\n         |label2=\n         |2={{clade\n            |1={{extinct}}''[[Eubelodon]]''\n            |label2= Brevirostrine clade\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''{{extinct}}[[Stegomastodon]]''\n               |label2=\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1={{extinct}}''[[Sinomastodon]]''\n                  |label2=\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1={{extinct}}'''''Notiomastodon'''''\n                     |label2=\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1={{extinct}}''[[Rhynchotherium]]'' \n                        |2={{extinct}}''[[Cuvieronius]]''\n                     }}\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n== Description ==\n[[List of gomphothere fossils in South America|Among many other specimens]], ''N. platensis'' is known from MECN 82, a 35-year-old male that would be around {{convert|2.52|m|abbr=on}} tall, with an estimated weight of {{convert|4.4|t|LT ST}}.<ref name=\"proboscideans\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Larramendi | first1 = A. | year = 2016 | title = Shoulder height, body mass and shape of proboscideans | journal = Acta Palaeontologica Polonica | volume = 61 | issue =  | pages =  | jstor =  | doi = 10.4202/app.00136.2014 | url = https://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app61/app001362014.pdf | format =  | accessdate = }}</ref> It had two tusks (one on either side of its trunk), like other members of the [[Gomphotheriidae]], and none on the lower jaw, as with other brevirostrine gomphotheres. Unlike close relative ''Cuvieronius'', its tusks were not twisted, but their length and shape are observed as greatly variable depending on the individual, as is morphology more generally<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" />[[File:Stegomastodon and Notiomastodon skeletals.png|thumb|Skeletons of ''[[Stegomastodon]]'' (left) and ''Notiomastodon'' (right)|alt=|center|440x440px]]\n== Paleobiogeography ==\n{{main|List of gomphothere fossils in South America}}\n''Notiomastodon'' has been described as the 'lowland gomphothere'.<ref name=\":0\" /> The genus tended to inhabit [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|seasonally dry, open forests]], with a range lining most of the South American coastline and lowland interior, bar the [[Guiana Shield]], with particularly large concentrations along the coast of [[Peru]] and in northeastern [[Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dantas|first=M\u00e1rio Andr\u00e9 Trindade|last2=Xavier|first2=M\u00e1rcia Cristina Teles|last3=Fran\u00e7a|first3=Lucas de Melo|last4=Cozzuol|first4=Mario Alberto|last5=Ribeiro|first5=Adauto de Souza|last6=Figueiredo|first6=Ana Maria Graciano|last7=Kinoshita|first7=Angela|last8=Baffa|first8=Oswaldo|date=2013-12-13|title=A review of the time scale and potential geographic distribution of Notiomastodon platensis (Ameghino, 1888) in the late Pleistocene of South America|url=https://www.ipen.br/biblioteca/2013/19588.pdf|journal=Quaternary International|series=Quaternary in South America: recent research initiatives|volume=317|pages=73\u201379|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2013.06.031|bibcode=2013QuInt.317...73D}}</ref> In contrast, the other representative of South American gomphotheres, ''[[Cuvieronius]]'', inhabited the mountainous [[Andes]] region from [[Ecuador]] to southern [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]], as well as lowland areas in north-east Peru.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\">{{cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2=dos Santos Avilla|first2=Leonardo|last3=Asevedo|first3=Lidiane|last4=Borges-Silva|first4= Leon|last5= Rosas|first5= Mariane|last6=Labarca-Encina|first6=Rafael|last7=Souberlich|first7= Ricardo|last8= Soibelzon|first8=Esteban|last9= Roman-Carrion|first9=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last10= R\u00edos|first10=Sergio D.|last11=Rincon|first11= Ascanio D.|last12=Cardoso de Oliveira|first12=Gina|last13=Pereira Lopes|first13=Renato |title=Sixty years after 'The mastodonts of Brazil': The state of the art of South American proboscideans (Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae)|journal=Quaternary International |volume=443|pages=52\u201364|date=30 September 2016|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2016.08.028|url=http://bibdigital.epn.edu.ec/bitstream/15000/17075/1/Moth%c3%a9%20et%20al.%2c%202016%20-%20Sixty%20years%20proboscideans.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe diet composition of ''Notiomastodon'' varied widely depending on location, but probably primarily consisted of a mix of [[C3 carbon fixation|C3]] [[shrub]]s and [[C4 carbon fixation|C4]] [[Poaceae|grasses]], whilst also serving as a primary disperser of the seeds for a variety of different plant species.<ref name=\"AsevedoWinck2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Asevedo|first1=Lidiane|last2=Winck|first2=Gisele R.|last3=Moth\u00e9|first3=Dimila|last4=Avilla|first4=Leonardo S.|title=Ancient diet of the Pleistocene gomphothere Notiomastodon platensis (Mammalia, Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae) from lowland mid-latitudes of South America: Stereomicrowear and tooth calculus analyses combined|journal=Quaternary International|volume=255|year=2012|pages=42\u201352|issn=1040-6182|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2011.08.037|bibcode=2012QuInt.255...42A}}</ref>\n\n== Behaviour ==\n''Notiomastodon'' was probably similar in population structure and behaviour to extant elephants.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2= Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Winck|first3=Gisele R.|date=26 November 2010|title=Population structure of the gomphothere Stegomastodon waringi (Mammalia: Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae) from the Pleistocene of Brazil|journal=Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ci\u00eancias|volume=82|issue=4|pages=983\u2013996|issn= 0001-3765|doi=10.1590/S0001-37652010005000001|pmid=21152772|url=http://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/8291/b6b312de01c1f12464743677d05f56f493a1.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Extinction ==\nIn 2019, a young specimen from Brazil was described with artifact embedded into its skull suggesting human hunting played a role in its extinction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=D.|last2=Avilla|first2=L.S.|last3=Ara\u00fajo-J\u00fanior|first3=H.I.|last4=Rotti|first4=A.|last5=Prous|first5=A.|last6=Azevedo|first6=S.A.K.|date=February 2020|title=An artifact embedded in an extinct proboscidean sheds new light on human-megafaunal interactions in the Quaternary of South America|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=229|pages=106125|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2019.106125|bibcode=2020QSRv..22906125M}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Proboscidea Genera}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2002264}}\n\n[[Category:Gomphotheres]]\n[[Category:Pliocene proboscideans]]<!-- range doesn't support this cat? -->\n[[Category:Pleistocene proboscideans]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of South America]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammal genera]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Holocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1929]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = ''Notiomastodon''\n| fossil_range = late [[Early Pleistocene]]-Early [[Holocene]] <br> (Possible Earliest Pleistocene record) <br>~{{Fossil range|0.8|0.011|earliest=2.5}}\n| image = Stegomastodon CCB.JPG\n| image2 = Stegomastodon platensis.JPG\n| image_width = 250px\n| image_caption = Skeleton at the Centro Cultural del Bicentenario de Santiago del Estero\n| image2_caption = Skull at the Natural History Museum, London\n| authority = Cabrera, 1929\n| taxon = Notiomastodon platensis\n| parent_authority = ([[Florentino Ameghino|Ameghino]], 1888) [originally ''Mastodon'']\n| synonyms = * ''Stegomastodon platensis'' <small>Ameghino 1888</small>\n* ''Stegomastodon waringi'' <small>Holland 1920</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon waringi'' <small>Holland 1920</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon chimborazi'' <small>Proa\u00f1o 1922</small>\n* ''Haplomastodon guayasensis'' <small>Hoffstetter 1952</small>\n* ''Amahuacatherium peruvium'' <small>Romero-Pittman 1996</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Notiomastodon''''' is an extinct [[proboscidea]]n genus of [[gomphothere]]s (a distant relative to modern [[elephants]]) endemic to [[South America]] from the [[Pleistocene]] to the [[Holocene]].<ref name=\"ShoshaniTassy2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Shoshani|first1=Jeheskel|last2=Tassy|first2=Pascal|title=Advances in proboscidean taxonomy & classification, anatomy & physiology, and ecology & behavior|journal=Quaternary International|volume=126\u2013128|year=2005|pages=5\u201320|issn=1040-6182|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2004.04.011|bibcode=2005QuInt.126....5S}}</ref> It was among the last known gomphotheres and one of two South American gomphotheres alongside ''[[Cuvieronius]]'' and was the predominant gomphothere on the continent ranging widely over most of South America excluding the [[Andes|High Andes]]. The species has a long and convoluted taxonomic history due to its morphological variability and confusion with related gomphothere taxa, which was only resolved during the 2010's.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n[[File:Gomphothere_Teeth_South_America_Cuvier_1806.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.56|Two gomphothere teeth from Cuvier (1806) with A referring to \u201c''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\u201d and B referring to \u201c''mastodonte humboldien''\u201d]]\nProboscideans in South America were first described by [[Georges Cuvier]] in 1806,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cuvier|first=Georges|title=Sur diff\u00e9rentes dents du genre des mastodontes, mais d'esp\u00e8ces moindres que celle de l'Ohio, trouv\u00e9es en plusieurs lieux des deux continents|journal=Annales du Mus\u00e9um d'Histoire Naturelle|volume=7|pages=401\u2013420|year=1806}}</ref> but he failed to give them specific names beyond \"Mastodon\".  [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim|Fischer]] in 1814 assigned the \u201c''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\u201d specimen the first specific name \"''Mastotherium hyodon''\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=Gotthelf|author-link=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim|title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata in Usum Praelectionem Academiae Imperialis Medico-Chirurgicae Mosquensis Edita: Vol 3. Classium, ordinum, generum illustratione perpetua aucta|trans-title=Illustrated Zoognosia in Synoptic Tables, Produced from Lectures in the Imperial Medico-Surgical Academy of Moscow by the Author, Gotthelf Fischer: Vol. 3, Classes, Orders, Genera, Enlarged Throughout with Illustration|edition=1|volume=3|publisher=Nikolai Sergeyevich Vsevolozhsky|location=Moscow|language=la|date=1813|url=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc}}</ref>{{rp|340}} In 1824, Cuvier classified the fossils of ''\"Mastodon andium\"'' as the \"''mastodonte des cordill\u00e8res''\" specimen, and  ''\"Mastodon humboldtii\"'' to the \"''mastodonte humboldien''\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Georges|last=Cuvier|title=Recherches sur les ossemens fossiles, ou l'on r\u00e9tablit les caract\u00e8res de plusieurs animaux dont les r\u00e9volutions du globe ont d\u00e9truit les esp\u00e8ces|date=1824|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/002004474|publisher=Chez G. Dufour et E. d'Ocagne}}</ref> Due to the [[Principle of Priority]], this meant that ''\"Mastodon andium\"'' was invalid, as \"''Mastotherium hyodon''\" was named first from the same specimen. Today, neither tooth is considered diagnostic to any specific taxon.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> \n\n\n''Notiomastodon'',{{refn|group=\"nb\"|From the {{lang-grc|\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}} ({{transl|grc|n\u00f3tios}}, \"southern\")<ref>{{LSJ|no/tios|\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2|ref}}</ref>}} \"southern mastodon\" was named by Cabrera (1929). It was assigned to the Gomphotheriidae by Carroll (1988).\n\nFor centuries, the taxonomy of gomphotheres, including ''Notiomastodon'' had been subject to debate, with many generic and specific names for similar South American gomphotheres. The species is currently under dispute, whether it should belong to ''Notiomastodon'' or ''[[Stegomastodon]]''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Perea|first=D.|last2=Alberdi|first2=M. T.|date=2015-12-30|title=Los gonfot\u00e9ridos (Mammalia, Proboscidea) de Uruguay: taxonom\u00eda, estratigraf\u00eda y cronolog\u00eda|journal=Estudios Geol\u00f3gicos|volume=71|issue=2|pages=e036|doi=10.3989/egeol.41864.346|issn=1988-3250|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /><ref name=\"Stegomastodon\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo|title=Mythbusting evolutionary issues on South American Gomphotheriidae (Mammalia: Proboscidea)|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|date= 15 February 2015|volume=110|pages=23\u201325|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2014.12.013}}</ref> as regardless of genus, the species is considered [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonymous]] with ''Haplomastodon'' by most authors, as the specimens were not considered morphologically distinct from this species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lucas|first=Spencer G.|last2=Yuan|first2=Wang|last3=Min|first3=Liu|date=2013-01-01|title=The palaeobiogeography of South American gomphotheres|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82348728.pdf|journal=Journal of Palaeogeography|volume=2|issue=1|pages=19\u201340|doi=10.3724/SP.J.1261.2013.00015|doi-broken-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref name=\"Moth\u00e9Avilla2012\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Cozzuol|first3=Mario A.|title=The South American Gomphotheres (Mammalia, Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae): Taxonomy, Phylogeny, and Biogeography|journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution|year=2012|issn=1064-7554|doi=10.1007/s10914-012-9192-3|volume=20|pages=23\u201332}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Cozzuol|first3=M\u00e1rio|last4=Winck|first4=Gisele R.|title=Taxonomic revision of the Quaternary gomphotheres (Mammalia: Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae) from the South American lowlands|journal=Quaternary International|volume=276\u2013277|pages=2\u20137|date= 25 October 2012|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2011.05.018|bibcode=2012QuInt.276....2M}}</ref> This article treats ''Notiomastodon'' separately because in phylogenetic analyses, ''Notiomastodon/Stegomastodon platensis'' specimens are not sister taxa, which would make the genus [[polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /><ref name=\"a\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Ferretti|first=Marco P.|title=Anatomy of Haplomastodon chimborazi (Mammalia, Proboscidea) from the late Pleistocene of Ecuador and its bearing on the phylogeny and systematics of south American gomphotheres|journal=Geodiversitas|volume=32|issue=4|pages=663\u2013721|date=2010|doi=10.5252/g2010n4a3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Ferretti|first2=Marco P.|last3=Avilla|first3=Leonardo S.|date=2017-06-03|title=Running Over the Same Old Ground: Stegomastodon Never Roamed South America|journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution|volume=26|issue=2|pages=165\u2013177|doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9392-y|issn=1064-7554}}</ref> However, some authors think this is inconclusive, as they think the North American ''Stegomastodon'' material is too scarce and fragmentary to make a definitive statement.<ref name=\"Stegomastodon\">{{cite journal|last=Labarca|first=R.|last2=Alberdi|first2=M.T.|last3=Prado|first3=J.L.|last4=Mansilla|first4=P.|last5=Mourgues|first5=F.A.|title=Nuevas evidencias acerca de la presencia de Stegomastodon platensis Ameghino, 1888, Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae, en el Pleistoceno tard\u00edo de Chile central/New evidences on the presence of Stegomastodon platensis Ameghino, 1888, Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae, in the Late Pleistocene of Central Chile|journal=Estudios Geol\u00f3gicos|volume=72|date=18 April 2016|url=http://estudiosgeol.revistas.csic.es/index.php/estudiosgeol/article/view/941/1075}}</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Evolution ==\n''Notiomastodon'' belongs to the family [[Gomphotheriidae]], a group of animals distantly related to modern elephants and [[mammoth]]s. ''Notiomastodon'' seems to have had a 4-million-year-long [[ghost lineage]], diverging from the clade that contains ''[[Rhynchotherium]]'' and ''[[Cuvieronius]]'' around the Late [[Miocene]]. This would imply that ''Notiomastodon'' had been evolving in southern [[Central America]], where the fossils are poorly sampled, prior to its migration into South America during the [[Pliocene]] or Pleistocene.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> Gomphotheres arrived in South America after the formation of the [[Isthmus of Panama]] as part of the [[Great American Interchange|Great American Biotic Interchange]], alongside many other taxa from North America. The oldest known record of gomphotheres in South America is a fragmentary vertebra from the Earliest Pleistocene (~2.5 Ma) [[Uquia Formation]] of Argentina<ref>Cione, A.L., Gasparini, G.M., Soibelzon, E., Soibelzon, L.H., Tonni, E.P., 2015. The Great American Biotic Interchange in Southern South America: Land Mammal Biostratigraphy, Climatic Evolution and Faunal Integration. Springer Briefs in Earth System Sciences. Springer, New York-London</ref> The oldest known remains definitively attributable to ''Notiomastodon'' are known from the late Early Pleistocene (1.2-0.8 ma) from the Rio de la Plata, also in Argentina, consisting of a pair of tusks and other associated remains.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" /> A 2019 study using [[collagen]] sequencing found ''Notiomastodon'' closer to ''[[Mastodon|Mammut]]'' than to extant elephants, though how this effects gomphothere phylogeny is unclear.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buckley|first=Michael|last2=Recabarren|first2=Omar P.|last3=Lawless|first3=Craig|last4=Garc\u00eda|first4=Nuria|last5=Pino|first5=Mario|date=November 2019|title=A molecular phylogeny of the extinct South American gomphothere through collagen sequence analysis|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=224|pages=105882|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2019.105882|bibcode=2019QSRv..22405882B|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Phylogeny ==\nThe phylogenetic position among trilophodont gomphotheres according to Moth\u00e9 et al., 2016 is:<ref name=a>{{cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=Dimila|last2=Ferretti|first2=Marco P.|last3=Avilla|first3=Leonardo S.|title=The Dance of Tusks: Rediscovery of Lower Incisors in the Pan-American Proboscidean ''Cuvieronius hyodon'' Revises Incisor Evolution in Elephantimorpha|journal=PLOS ONE|date=12 January 2016|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147009|pmid=26756209|pmc=4710528|volume=11|issue=1|page=e0147009|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147009M}}</ref>\n\n{{clade\n   |label1={{extinct}}[[Gomphotheriidae]] (Gomphotheres)\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{extinct}}''[[Gomphotherium]]''\n      |label2=\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{extinct}}''[[Gnathabelodon]]''\n         |label2=\n         |2={{clade\n            |1={{extinct}}''[[Eubelodon]]''\n            |label2= Brevirostrine clade\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''{{extinct}}[[Stegomastodon]]''\n               |label2=\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1={{extinct}}''[[Sinomastodon]]''\n                  |label2=\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1={{extinct}}'''''Notiomastodon'''''\n                     |label2=\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1={{extinct}}''[[Rhynchotherium]]'' \n                        |2={{extinct}}''[[Cuvieronius]]''\n                     }}\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n== Description ==\n[[List of gomphothere fossils in South America|Among many other specimens]], ''N. platensis'' is known from MECN 82, a 35-year-old male that would be around {{convert|2.52|m|abbr=on}} tall, with an estimated weight of {{convert|4.4|t|LT ST}}.<ref name=\"proboscideans\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Larramendi | first1 = A. | year = 2016 | title = Shoulder height, body mass and shape of proboscideans | journal = Acta Palaeontologica Polonica | volume = 61 | issue =  | pages =  | jstor =  | doi = 10.4202/app.00136.2014 | url = https://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app61/app001362014.pdf | format =  | accessdate = }}</ref> It had two tusks (one on either side of its trunk), like other members of the [[Gomphotheriidae]], and none on the lower jaw, as with other brevirostrine gomphotheres. Unlike close relative ''Cuvieronius'', its tusks were not twisted, but their length and shape are observed as greatly variable depending on the individual, as is morphology more generally<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\" />[[File:Stegomastodon and Notiomastodon skeletals.png|thumb|Skeletons of ''[[Stegomastodon]]'' (left) and ''Notiomastodon'' (right)|alt=|center|440x440px]]\n== Paleobiogeography ==\n{{main|List of gomphothere fossils in South America}}\n''Notiomastodon'' has been described as the 'lowland gomphothere'.<ref name=\":0\" /> The genus tended to inhabit [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|seasonally dry, open forests]], with a range lining most of the South American coastline and lowland interior, bar the [[Guiana Shield]], with particularly large concentrations along the coast of [[Peru]] and in northeastern [[Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dantas|first=M\u00e1rio Andr\u00e9 Trindade|last2=Xavier|first2=M\u00e1rcia Cristina Teles|last3=Fran\u00e7a|first3=Lucas de Melo|last4=Cozzuol|first4=Mario Alberto|last5=Ribeiro|first5=Adauto de Souza|last6=Figueiredo|first6=Ana Maria Graciano|last7=Kinoshita|first7=Angela|last8=Baffa|first8=Oswaldo|date=2013-12-13|title=A review of the time scale and potential geographic distribution of Notiomastodon platensis (Ameghino, 1888) in the late Pleistocene of South America|url=https://www.ipen.br/biblioteca/2013/19588.pdf|journal=Quaternary International|series=Quaternary in South America: recent research initiatives|volume=317|pages=73\u201379|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2013.06.031|bibcode=2013QuInt.317...73D}}</ref> In contrast, the other representative of South American gomphotheres, ''[[Cuvieronius]]'', inhabited the mountainous [[Andes]] region from [[Ecuador]] to southern [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]], as well as lowland areas in north-east Peru.<ref name=\"Moth\u00e9 et al 2016 (In Press)\">{{cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2=dos Santos Avilla|first2=Leonardo|last3=Asevedo|first3=Lidiane|last4=Borges-Silva|first4= Leon|last5= Rosas|first5= Mariane|last6=Labarca-Encina|first6=Rafael|last7=Souberlich|first7= Ricardo|last8= Soibelzon|first8=Esteban|last9= Roman-Carrion|first9=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last10= R\u00edos|first10=Sergio D.|last11=Rincon|first11= Ascanio D.|last12=Cardoso de Oliveira|first12=Gina|last13=Pereira Lopes|first13=Renato |title=Sixty years after 'The mastodonts of Brazil': The state of the art of South American proboscideans (Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae)|journal=Quaternary International |volume=443|pages=52\u201364|date=30 September 2016|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2016.08.028|url=http://bibdigital.epn.edu.ec/bitstream/15000/17075/1/Moth%c3%a9%20et%20al.%2c%202016%20-%20Sixty%20years%20proboscideans.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe diet composition of ''Notiomastodon'' varied widely depending on location, but probably primarily consisted of a mix of [[C3 carbon fixation|C3]] [[shrub]]s and [[C4 carbon fixation|C4]] [[Poaceae|grasses]], whilst also serving as a primary disperser of the seeds for a variety of different plant species.<ref name=\"AsevedoWinck2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Asevedo|first1=Lidiane|last2=Winck|first2=Gisele R.|last3=Moth\u00e9|first3=Dimila|last4=Avilla|first4=Leonardo S.|title=Ancient diet of the Pleistocene gomphothere Notiomastodon platensis (Mammalia, Proboscidea, Gomphotheriidae) from lowland mid-latitudes of South America: Stereomicrowear and tooth calculus analyses combined|journal=Quaternary International|volume=255|year=2012|pages=42\u201352|issn=1040-6182|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2011.08.037|bibcode=2012QuInt.255...42A}}</ref>\n\n== Behaviour ==\n''Notiomastodon'' was probably similar in population structure and behaviour to extant elephants.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Moth\u00e9|first1=Dimila|last2= Avilla|first2=Leonardo S.|last3=Winck|first3=Gisele R.|date=26 November 2010|title=Population structure of the gomphothere Stegomastodon waringi (Mammalia: Proboscidea: Gomphotheriidae) from the Pleistocene of Brazil|journal=Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ci\u00eancias|volume=82|issue=4|pages=983\u2013996|issn= 0001-3765|doi=10.1590/S0001-37652010005000001|pmid=21152772|url=http://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/8291/b6b312de01c1f12464743677d05f56f493a1.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Extinction ==\nIn 2019, a young specimen from Brazil was described with artifact embedded into its skull suggesting human hunting played a role in its extinction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moth\u00e9|first=D.|last2=Avilla|first2=L.S.|last3=Ara\u00fajo-J\u00fanior|first3=H.I.|last4=Rotti|first4=A.|last5=Prous|first5=A.|last6=Azevedo|first6=S.A.K.|date=February 2020|title=An artifact embedded in an extinct proboscidean sheds new light on human-megafaunal interactions in the Quaternary of South America|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=229|pages=106125|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2019.106125|bibcode=2020QSRv..22906125M}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Proboscidea Genera}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2002264}}\n\n[[Category:Gomphotheres]]\n[[Category:Pliocene proboscideans]]<!-- range doesn't support this cat? -->\n[[Category:Pleistocene proboscideans]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of South America]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammal genera]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Holocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1929]]\n", "name_user": "Hemiauchenia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Notiomastodon"}
{"title_page": "Bobrek-Karf Municipality", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Bobrek-Karf\n| other_name = Gemeinde Bobrek-Karf, Gemeinde Bobrek\n| image_skyline =\n| imagesize =\n| settlement_type = [[Municipalities of Germany|Gemeinde]]\n| total_type = Total\n| image_flag =\n| image_shield =\n| image_map =\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = \n* [[File:Flag of Germany (3-2 aspect ratio).svg|20px]] [[Weimar Republic|German Reich]] (1928-1933)\n* [[File:Flag of Germany (1935\u20131945).svg|20px]] [[Nazi Germany|German Reich]] (1933-1945)\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces of Prussia|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Province of Silesia|Silesia]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Germany|Rural District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Bytom|Beuthen]]-[[Tarnowskie G\u00f3ry|Tarnowitz]] District\n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| area_total_km2 =\n| population_total = 22095 | population_as_of = 1939\n| population_density_km2 =\n| population_urban = \n| population_blank1_title =\n| population_blank =\n| coor_pinpoint =\n| coordinates =\n| seat = [[Bobrek, Bytom|Bobrek]]\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Gemeinde Bobrek-Karf''', also referred to as simply '''Gemeinde Bobrek''' or '''Gemeinde Karf-Bobrek'''\n([[Upper_Silesia#Ethnolinguistic_structure_before_the_plebiscite|Polish]]: ''Gmina Bobrek-Karb'', ''Gmina Bobrek'', ''Gmina Karb-Bobrek''<ref name=\"auto1\">[http://www.sbc.org.pl/Content/172186/iv4414-1928-81-0001.pdf]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref>), was a [[Municipalities of Germany|municipality]] in the District of [[Bytom|Beuthen-]][[Tarnowskie G\u00f3ry|Tarnowitz]], part of the [[Province of Silesia|Silesian Province]] of Germany. It was created following the unification of the [[Bobrek Municipality|Bobrek]] and [[Karf Municipality|Karf]] municipalities in 1928.\n\n==History==\nThe unification of the municipalities of [[Karf Municipality|Karf]] and [[Bobrek Municipality|Bobrek]] was proclaimed in 1928<ref name=\"auto1\"/>, the result was the creation of the '''Bobrek-Karf Municipality'''.\n\nIn 1932 a [[Evangelical-Augstan Church in Bobrek, Bytom|wooden evangelical church]] was built in Bobrek.\n\nThe municipality was abolished in 1945 following the [[Territorial changes of Poland immediately after World War II|Polish takeover]] of Bobrek and Karf, in its place a new municipality (Gmina Bobrek) was created (later renamed to \"Gmina Bobrek-Karb\").\n\n==Demographics==\nPopulation of the municipality (Gemeinde) of Bobrek-Karf<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://treemagic.org/rademacher/www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/beuthen.html|title=Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Schlesien, Beuthen|website=treemagic.org}}</ref>:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!&nbsp; ||colspan=2| Population\n|-\n|''Year'' || ''Number''\n|-\n|1933 || '''21974'''\n|-\n|1939 || '''22095'''\n|-\n|}\nReligious beliefs in Bobrek-Karf<ref name=\"auto\"/>:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!&nbsp; ||colspan=2| Catholicism ||colspan=3|Evangelicalism||colspan=4|Other Christian denominations||colspan=5|Judaism\n|-\n|1933||colspan=2|'''20773'''||colspan=3|'''1057'''||colspan=4|'''4'''||colspan=5|'''40'''\n|-\n|1939||colspan=2|'''20845'''||colspan=3|'''1094'''||colspan=4|'''18'''||colspan=5|'''2'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://treemagic.org/rademacher/www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/beuthen.html Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Schlesien, Beuthen]\n*[http://www.territorial.de/obschles/beuthtar/gem1945.htm Gemeindeverzeichnis Landkreis Beuthen-Tarnowitz [Stand: 1. 1. 1945]]\n*[http://www.sbc.org.pl/Content/172186/iv4414-1928-81-0001.pdf Data]\n\n[[Category:Bytom]]\n[[Category:Province of Silesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Bobrek-Karf\n| other_name = Gemeinde Bobrek-Karf, Gemeinde Bobrek\n| image_skyline =\n| imagesize =\n| settlement_type = [[Municipalities of Germany|Gemeinde]]\n| total_type = Total\n| image_flag =\n| image_shield =\n| image_map =\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = \n* [[File:Flag of Germany (3-2 aspect ratio).svg|20px]] [[Weimar Republic|German Reich]] (1928-1933)\n* [[File:Flag of Germany (1935\u20131945).svg|20px]] [[Nazi Germany|German Reich]] (1933-1945)\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces of Prussia|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Province of Silesia|Silesia]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Germany|Rural District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Bytom|Beuthen]]-[[Tarnowskie G\u00f3ry|Tarnowitz]] District\n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| area_total_km2 =\n| population_total = 22095 | population_as_of = 1939\n| population_density_km2 =\n| population_urban = \n| population_blank1_title =\n| population_blank =\n| coor_pinpoint =\n| coordinates =\n| seat = [[Bobrek, Bytom|Bobrek]]\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Gemeinde Bobrek-Karf''', also referred to as simply '''Gemeinde Bobrek''' or '''Gemeinde Karf-Bobrek'''\n([[Upper_Silesia#Ethnolinguistic_structure_before_the_plebiscite|Polish]]: ''Gmina Bobrek-Karb'', ''Gmina Bobrek'', ''Gmina Karb-Bobrek''<ref name=\"auto1\">[http://www.sbc.org.pl/Content/172186/iv4414-1928-81-0001.pdf]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref>), was a [[Municipalities of Germany|municipality]] in the District of [[Bytom|Beuthen-]][[Tarnowskie G\u00f3ry|Tarnowitz]], part of the [[Province of Silesia|Silesian Province]] of Germany. It was created following the unification of the [[Bobrek Municipality|Bobrek]] and [[Karf Municipality|Karf]] municipalities in 1928.\n\n==History==\nThe unification of the municipalities of [[Karf Municipality|Karf]] and [[Bobrek Municipality|Bobrek]] was proclaimed in 1928<ref name=\"auto1\"/>, the result was the creation of the '''Bobrek-Karf Municipality'''.\n\nIn 1932 a [[Evangelical-Augstan Church in Bobrek, Bytom|wooden evangelical church]] was built in Bobrek.\n\nThe municipality was abolished in 1945 following the [[Territorial changes of Poland immediately after World War II|Polish takeover]] of Bobrek and Karf, in its place a new municipality (Gmina Bobrek) was created (later renamed to \"Gmina Bobrek-Karb\").\n\n==Demographics==\nPopulation of the municipality (Gemeinde) of Bobrek-Karf<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://treemagic.org/rademacher/www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/beuthen.html|title=Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Schlesien, Beuthen|website=treemagic.org}}</ref>:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!&nbsp; ||colspan=2| Population\n|-\n|''Year'' || ''Number''\n|-\n|1933 || '''21974'''\n|-\n|1939 || '''22095'''\n|-\n|}\nReligious beliefs in Bobrek-Karf<ref name=\"auto\"/>:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!&nbsp; ||colspan=2| Catholicism ||colspan=3|Evangelicalism||colspan=4|Other Christian denominations||colspan=5|Judaism\n|-\n|1933||colspan=2|'''20773'''||colspan=3|'''1057'''||colspan=4|'''4'''||colspan=5|'''40'''\n|-\n|1939||colspan=2|'''20845'''||colspan=3|'''1094'''||colspan=4|'''18'''||colspan=5|'''2'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://treemagic.org/rademacher/www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/beuthen.html Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Schlesien, Beuthen]\n*[http://www.territorial.de/obschles/beuthtar/gem1945.htm Gemeindeverzeichnis Landkreis Beuthen-Tarnowitz [Stand: 1. 1. 1945]]\n*[http://www.sbc.org.pl/Content/172186/iv4414-1928-81-0001.pdf Data]\n\n[[Category:Bytom]]\n", "name_user": "He\u0142mPolski", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobrek-Karf_Municipality"}
{"title_page": "Peter Early", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          =  Peter Early\n|image         = GovernorPeterEarly.jpg\n|caption       = \n|order         =  [[List of Governors of Georgia|28th Governor of Georgia]]\n|lieutenant    =\n|term_start    = November 5, 1813\n|term_end      = November 20, 1815\n|predecessor   = [[David Brydie Mitchell]]\n|successor     = David Brydie Mitchell\n| state1       = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| district1    = [[Georgia's at-large congressional district|at-large]]\n| term_start1  = January 10, 1803\n| term_end1    = March 3, 1807\n| preceded1    = [[John Milledge]]\n| succeeded1   = [[Howell Cobb (born 1772)|Howell Cobb]]\n|birth_name   = Peter Early\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1773|6|20}}\n|birth_place  = [[Madison, Virginia|Madison]], [[Colony of Virginia]], [[British America]]\n|death_date   =  {{death date and age|1817|8|15|1773|6|20}}\n|death_place  = [[Scull Shoals, Georgia|Scull Shoals]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|party        = [[Democratic-Republican Party]]\n|spouse       = \n|children     = \n|alma_mater   = [[Washington and Lee University]]<br>[[Princeton University]]\n|religion     =\n}}\n\n'''Peter Early''' (June 20, 1773 \u2013 August 15, 1817) was an [[United States|American]] lawyer, jurist and politician.\n\n[[File:19-13-156-museum.jpg|thumb|Bust of Early at the [[Washington-Wilkes Historical Museum]]]]\n\n==Early life==\n\nHe was born near [[Madison, Virginia|Madison]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]], in 1773, the son of Joel Early and Lucy Smith.  He had a sister Lucy, who later married [[Mathews family|Charles Lewis Mathews]].<ref name=Patrick>Patrick, Rembert W. (2010). ''Florida Fiasco: Rampant Rebels on the Georgia-Florida Border, 1810-1815''. University of Georgia Press, 2010. {{ISBN|0820335495}}, 9780820335490</ref> His cousin, Jubal Early, became the grandfather of [[Jubal Early|Jubal Anderson Early]] (1816\u20131894), later a prominent Confederate general. \n\nPeter Early graduated from the Lexington Academy (current-day [[Washington and Lee University]]). He later graduated from [[Princeton College]], in 1792. His family moved to [[Wilkes County, Georgia]], on the central eastern border, that same year. Early was [[reading law|studying law]] with [[Jared Ingersoll]] in [[Philadelphia]]. After finishing his legal studies, Peter Early joined his family in Wilkes County. \n\nThere he married Ann Adams Smith in 1793. In 1796 he began his [[practice of law|law practice]] in [[Washington, Georgia|Washington]], the county seat of Wilkes County.\n\n==Political life==\n\nEarly was elected as a [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] from Georgia to the [[8th United States Congress]] to serve the remainder of the term left vacant by the resignation of [[John Milledge]], who had been elected as Governor of Georgia. Early was re-elected to the [[9th United States Congress|9th Congress]]. During his congressional service, Early was one of the managers of the prosecution in the [[impeachment]] trials against [[John Pickering (judge)|John Pickering]], [[United States District Court for the District of New Hampshire|New Hampshire United States District Court judge]], in January 1804, and [[Samuel Chase]], [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court]], in December of that year. Early did not seek re-election in 1806.\n\nAfter his congressional service,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Early|first1=Peter|title=Letter, 1806 Apr. 19, Washington City, [to] Governor [John] Milledge / Peter Early|url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/zlna/id:tcc380|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> Early was elected by the [[Georgia General Assembly]] as judge of the Superior Court, Ocmulgee Circuit, serving in that court from 1807 until 1813. The respect and popularity he gained from his service on the bench propelled him to be elected the [[List of Governors of Georgia|28th Governor of Georgia]] in 1813. He served one term, through 1815, during which he was instrumental in committing funds on several occasions from the state treasury to help raise and supply additional troops from Georgia to the [[United States|American]] military forces during the latter half of the [[War of 1812]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Early|first1=Peter|title=[Letter], 1813 Nov. [to] Gen[era]l [David B.?] Mitchell / Peter Early|url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/zlna/id:tcc414|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nEarly moved to [[Greene County, Georgia|Greene County]] after his gubernatorial term, where he was elected to the [[Georgia Senate]].\n\n==Death==\nDuring his term in the Georgia Senate, Peter Early died on August 15, 1817, at his summer home near Scull Shoals in Greene County. He was buried on the west bank of the [[Oconee River]] near his Fontenoy Plantation home,<ref>{{cite web|title=Governor Peter Early historical marker|url=http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/greene/governor-peter-early|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> with a simple monument to mark his grave.\n\nIn 1914, his family had his remains reinterred in the [[Greensboro, Georgia|Greensboro]] City Cemetery.\n\n==Legacy and honors==\n[[Early County, Georgia]],<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n111 112]}}</ref> and Fort Early<ref>{{cite web|title=Fort Early historical marker|url=http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/crisp/fort-early|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> were named in his honor.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|title=Communication of His Excellency the Governor to the Legislature of Georgia: with a part of the accompanying documents|date=1815|publisher=S. & F. Grantland|location=Milledgeville, Ga.|url=http://digitalcollections.library.gsu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/printed/id/1964|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}\n*{{cite book\n |editor=[[William J. Northen]]\n |title=Men of Mark in Georgia\n |url=https://archive.org/details/menmarkingeorgi00nortgoog\n |quote=Georgia Scenes.\n |format=PDF\n |accessdate=December 28, 2006\n |edition=Volume II\n |year=1910\n |publisher=A. B. Caldwell\n |location=Atlanta, Georgia\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/menmarkingeorgi00nortgoog/page/n433 353]\u2013356\n }}\n{{CongBio|E000014}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061123175249/http://www.georgiaarchives.org/what_do_we_have/govhisroster.htm Georgia State Archives Roster of State Governors]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060118235505/http://www.gashpo.org/assets/documents/ga_govs_graves_field_guide.pdf ''Georgia Governor's Gravesites Field Guide (1776-2003)'']\n*[http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/greene/governor-peter-early Governor Peter Early] historical marker\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state = Georgia\n|district = AL\n|before= [[John Milledge]]\n|after= [[Howell Cobb (Elder)|Howell Cobb]]\n|years=January 10, 1803 \u2013 March 3, 1807\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[David Brydie Mitchell]]\n|title=[[List of governors of Georgia|Governor of Georgia]]\n|years=November 5, 1813 \u2013 November 20, 1815\n|after=[[David Brydie Mitchell]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Georgia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Early, Peter}}\n[[Category:1773 births]]\n[[Category:1817 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n