me=WhoWeAreTraditions/></small>\n| ratio = 5:1<ref name=WhoWeAre/>\n| classes_offered = 224<ref name=WhoWeAre/>\n| schedule = Semester\n| athletics = 19 interscholastic sports<ref name=WhoWeAre/>\n| mascot = Bearcat<ref name=Athletics>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotchkiss.org/athletics/index.aspx|title=Athletics: Bearcat Athletics|publisher=The Hotchkiss School|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n| SAT = 2110 <small>(2014)</small><ref name=SAT-HuffPostJan2014>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/23/schools-highest-sat-scores_n_4654077.html|title=The High Schools With The Highest SAT/ACT Scores In The Nation|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n| newspaper = The Record<ref name=StudentLife/>\n| yearbook = The Mischianza<ref name=StudentLife/>\n| class = 13 students\n| campus = [[Rural]], {{convert|827|acre|km2|0}}<br><small>13 dorms, 2 lakes, 1 forest</small><ref name=WhoWeAre/>\n| colors = {{color box|#000066}} [[Yale Blue]] and <br>{{Color box|white|border=darkgray}} White\n| rivals = [[Taft School]]<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/><ref name=Taft>{{cite web|url=http://www.taftschool.org/news/onephotoleft.aspx?storyname=HotchkissDay2011|title=Taft-Hotchkiss Rivalry Heats Up: Saturday is Hotchkiss Day: Show your spirit!|publisher=[[Taft School]]|accessdate=November 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129205605/http://www.taftschool.org/news/onephotoleft.aspx?storyname=HotchkissDay2011|archivedate=November 29, 2014}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"It is Spirit Week on campus as the excitement builds for Hotchkiss Day this Saturday, November 12. It will be an exciting day for Taft sports, as many of our teams travel north in the hopes of extending their winning records and defending Taft\u2019s name against our perennial rival.\" \u2014 \u00b6 1</ref>\n| affiliation = <small>[[Eight Schools Association]]<ref name=EightSchoolsAssociation/><br>[[Ten Schools Admissions Organization]]<ref name=TenSchools/><br>[[G20 Schools]]<br>[[Founders League]]<ref name=FoundersLeague/><br>[[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC)<ref name=NEPSAC/><br>[[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]] (NEASC)<ref name=NEASC/><br>The Association of Boarding Schools (TABS)<ref name=TABS/><br>Global Education Benchmark Group (GEBG)<ref name=GEBG/><br>[[Round Square (educational organisation)|Round Square]]<ref name=RoundSquare/><br>[[Green Schools Alliance]]<ref name=GreenSchools/></small>\n| endowment = $491.8 million <small>(June 2019)</small>\n| annual_tuition = $59,990 (boarding)<ref name=Tuition>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotchkiss.org/admission/tuition-financial-aid|title=Tuition and Payments &#124; Private School CT &#124; The Hotchkiss School|website=www.hotchkiss.org|accessdate=Aug 31, 2019}}</ref><br>$50,990 (day)\n| free_label_1 = Former pupils\n| free_1 = Pythians (even entrance year) or Olympians (odd entrance year)\n| homepage = {{URL|hotchkiss.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hotchkiss School''' is a private, nonsectarian, coeducational [[University-preparatory school|college preparatory]] [[boarding school]] in [[Lakeville, Connecticut]]. Founded in 1891, the school offers a [[classical education movement|classical education]]<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/> with grades 9\u201312 and a postgraduate (PG) option, attracting students across the United States and 34 foreign countries.<ref name=\"WhoWeAre\"/>\n\nHotchkiss is a member of the [[Eight Schools Association]],<ref name=EightSchoolsAssociation>{{cite web|url=http://thenews.choate.edu/article/eight-schools-association-who-what-when-where-why|title=The Eight Schools Association: Who? What? When? Where? Why?|first=Josh|last=Kim|publisher=[[Choate Rosemary Hall]]|date=May 14, 2010|accessdate=November 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129033359/http://thenews.choate.edu/article/eight-schools-association-who-what-when-where-why|archivedate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> Ten Schools Admissions Organization,<ref name=TenSchools>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenschools.org/page.cfm?p=360|title=About: Member School Directory|publisher=[[Ten Schools Admissions Organization]]|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> [[G20 Schools]] group, [[Founders League]],<ref name=FoundersLeague>{{cite web|url=http://foundersleagueathletics.org|title=Founders League: Member Schools|publisher=[[Founders League]]|date=|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC),<ref name=NEPSAC>{{cite web|url=http://www.nepsac.org/page/2845|title=ABOUT NEPSAC: Member Schools|publisher=[[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]]|date=|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> [[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]] (NEASC),<ref name=NEASC>{{cite web|url=https://cis.neasc.org/cis-directory-of-schools/hotchkiss-school|title=About Us: CIS Directory of Schools|publisher=[[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]]|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> The Association of Boarding Schools (TABS),<ref name=TABS>{{cite web|url=http://www.boardingschools.com/school-profile/The-Hotchkiss-School|title=School Profile: The Hotchkiss School|publisher=The Association of Boarding Schools (TABS)|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> [[National Association of Independent Schools]],<ref name=NAIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nais.org/Magazines-Newsletters/ISMagazine/Pages/Sustainability-educators-convene-at-Hotchkiss-for-environmental-summit.aspx|title=Sustainability educators convene at Hotchkiss for environmental summit|first=Ari|last=Pinkus|publisher=[[National Association of Independent Schools]]|date=Fall 2013|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Global Education Benchmark Group (GEBG),<ref name=GEBG>{{cite web|url=http://gebg.org/members/|title=Member Schools|publisher=Global Education Benchmark Group (GEBG)|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> [[Round Square (educational organisation)|Round Square]],<ref name=RoundSquare>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/perch/resources/rsis-south-africa-project-report-2011.pdf|title=RSIS South Africa Project - July 2011: Leader's Report|first=Damien|last=Vassallo|publisher=[[Round Square (educational organisation)|Round Square]]|date=August 2011|accessdate=November 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129040800/http://www.roundsquare.org/perch/resources/rsis-south-africa-project-report-2011.pdf|archivedate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Cum Laude Society]],<ref name=CumLaude>{{cite web|url=http://www.cumlaudesociety.org/about-cls.htm|title=About CLS: Member Schools|publisher=[[Cum Laude Society]]|date=2014|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> and [[Green Schools Alliance]].<ref name=GreenSchools>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenschoolsalliance.org/schoolprofile/hotchkiss-school|title=Membership - School Profiles: The Hotchkiss School|publisher=[[Green Schools Alliance]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093014/http://www.greenschoolsalliance.org/schoolprofile/hotchkiss-school|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most selective high schools in the country, Hotchkiss has an 18% admit rate.<ref name=Endow-AdmitRateJuly2013>{{cite web |url=https://www.hotchkiss.org/uploaded/documents/ABOUT/Hotchkiss-18-19_Facts_Figures.pdf |title=Head of School: Leadership Opportunity - July 2013 |publisher=The Hotchkiss School |date=July 2013 }}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"...Value of Endowment: $455M.\" \u2014 Pg. 2\n*<sup>b</sup> \"Approximately 18% of the 1,860 applicants were offered admission this year.\" \u2014 Pg. 5, \u00b6 3</ref> Moreover, the school has one of the largest private school [[financial endowment|endowment]]s in the country at nearly $500 million (ranked fifth largest in 2008 by ''[[The New York Times]]'').<ref name=Endow430M-NYT2008>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/26/business/26prep.html?_r=0&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1416448933-/pqsaBZX7z3hCjbbjNL1ZQ&pagewanted=all|title=Age of Riches: At Elite Prep Schools, College-Size Endowments|first=Geraldine|last=Fabrikant|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=January 26, 2008|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"Educational Wealth: Some independent schools have accumulated sizeable endowments. Here are some of the largest, at the end of the schools' most recent fiscal year...Hotchkiss School, Lakeville, Conn. 430.0.\" \u2014 Pg. 1, Inforgraphic</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PostcardLakevilleCTHotchkissSchool1901to1907UndividedBack.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Postcard circa 1905]]\nIn 1891, [[Maria Bissell Hotchkiss|Maria Harrison Bissell Hotchkiss]], with guidance from Yale President [[Timothy Dwight V]], founded the school to prepare young men for [[Yale University]]. In 1892, The Hotchkiss School opened its doors to 50 male boarding students for $600. Hotchkiss's endowment also precipitated scholarship aid to deserving students. In 1974, the school became coeducational.<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotchkiss.org/AboutHotchkiss/HistoryTra.aspx |title=About Hotchkiss: History & Traditions |publisher=Hotchkiss School |date=2014 |accessdate=November 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120040039/http://www.hotchkiss.org/AboutHotchkiss/HistoryTra.aspx |archivedate=November 20, 2014 }}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"With the guidance of then President of Yale University Timothy Dwight, Maria Hotchkiss established the School in 1891 to prepare young men for Yale...Hotchkiss offers a classical education, finding strength in a traditional approach that has worked well and stood the test of time.\" \u2014 \u00b6 2 (Strengthened by Time)\n*<sup>b</sup> \"The week leading up to and including \u201cTaft Day,\" the Saturday in the fall when Hotchkiss teams compete against the Taft School. From kickoff night to the Friday night pep rally and bonfire to Taft Day itself, blue and white rule.\" \u2014 \u00b6 14 (Sprit Day, right sidebar)\n*<sup>c</sup> \"When the Hotchkiss School opened its doors in 1892, the first 50 boys were charged a boarding tuition of $600--more than many families could afford. But fortunately, Maria Hotchkiss had insisted on something unique in allocating the funds to establish the School: Hotchkiss would offer scholarship aid to deserving students.\" \u2014 \u00b6 3 (A 123-Year Policy)\n*<sup>d</sup> \"Three years later, in September 1974, 88 young women entered Hotchkiss as preps, lower-mids, upper-mids, and seniors. Today, the number of boys and girls attending Hotchkiss is roughly equal.\" \u2014 \u00b6 4 (Coeducation)\n*<sup>e</sup> \"As early as 1912 students from China have come to Hotchkiss...He also enabled Hotchkiss students to study abroad by having the School join the English-Speaking Union program and through the inception of the International Schoolboy Exchange in 1928. Today, the Hotchkiss student body includes students from 34 countries, and on average 5 to 10 students study abroad each year with the School Year Abroad program. Begun by the Class of 1948, The Fund for Global Understanding provides grant support for students participating in summer community service projects throughout the world. Hotchkiss is also a member of Round Square and Global Connections...\" \u2014 \u00b6 5 (Globally Connected)\n*<sup>f</sup> \"From the beginning, Maria Hotchkiss was not interested in establishing \u201ca school for the pampered sons of rich gentlemen.\u201d...In the 1960s Hotchkiss began its first formal participation in minority student recruitment programs such as the U.S. Grant Program \u2013 begun by Hotchkiss graduates attending Yale \u2013 as well as A Better Chance (ABC) and the Greater Opportunity (GO) Program. The Hotchkiss connection with Prep for Prep, an organization that helps prepare minority students for academically demanding independent schools, began in the early 1980s. Today, 43 percent of Hotchkiss students identify themselves as students of color.\" \u2014 \u00b6 6 (Lessons of Differences)\n*<sup>g</sup> \"Of our 600 students, 21 percent come from countries other than the U.S.\"\u2014 \u00b6 8 (Hotchkiss Today)</ref>\n\n===Number-one rule===\nGeorge Van Santvoord (g. 1908, Yale 1912),<ref name=VanS-Alumnus>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotchkiss.org/alumni/closerlook.aspx?id=4|title=Alumni Accomplishments - A Closer Look: George Van Santvoord '08|first=John G.|last=Bowen|publisher=Hotchkiss School|accessdate=March 28, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122840/http://www.hotchkiss.org/alumni/closerlook.aspx?id=4|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> a headmaster hailed as the Duke with an honorary dorm, claimed there was only one school rule: \"Be a gentleman.\"<ref name=Rule-Kolowrat>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HQ3-AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=%22Be+a+gentleman%22+hotchkiss#v=snippet&q=%22Be%20a%20gentleman%22&f=false|title=Hotchkiss: A Chronicle of an American School|first=Ernest|last=Kolowrat|publisher=Hotchkiss School|date=1992|accessdate=March 28, 2015|isbn=9781461700180}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"Be a gentleman! That was the only rule, the Duke always liked to say, that the school truly had.\"\u2014 Pg. 33, \u00b6 2</ref><ref name=Rule-AmSecretAristocracy>{{cite web|url=http://www.scholarisland.org/manners.htm|title=America's Secret Aristocracy|first=Stephen|last=Birmingham|publisher=[[Little, Brown and Company]]|date=1987|accessdate=March 28, 2015}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"His school, the Duke used to say (Hotchkiss) had only one rule, and that was \"Be a gentleman,\" How he defined what a gentleman was he did not say, but what a gentleman was usually became clear when you discovered what a gentleman wasn't. A gentleman didn't cheat. he didn't lie. A gentleman wasn't petty. A gentleman wasn't intolerant of others' shortcomings. A gentleman wasn't a whiner, wasn't a gossip, wasn't a boor, wasn't inconsiderate of others' feelings...\"</ref><ref name=Rule-AmLegends>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanlegends.com/interviews/rector_of_justin.html|title=American Legends Interviews - Louis Auchincloss: The Rector of Justin|first=|last=|publisher=American Legends|date=|accessdate=March 28, 2015}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"George Van Santvoord (1891-1975), whose distinguished bearing earned him the nickname the Duke. Van Santvoord, and his predecessor who was known as the King, claimed that at Hotchkiss there was only one rule for students to follow: Be a gentleman.\"\u2014 \u00b6 2</ref><ref name=Rule-HotchkissMag2014>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/thehotchkissschool/docs/14sum_hotchkissmagazine|title=Hotchkiss Magazine: Summer 2014|first=David D.|last=Shields|publisher=Hotchkiss School|date=Summer 2014|accessdate=March 28, 2015}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"And the number-one rule in the ''Blue Book''\u2014Be a gentleman.\"\u2014 Pg. 24, last \u00b6</ref> In 1954, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' recognized in \"Education: The Duke Steps Down\", that \"of all U.S. prep schools, few, if any, can beat the standards Hotchkiss has set.\"<ref name=TIME-1954>{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,823665,00.html|title=Education: The Duke Steps Down|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|date=November 1, 1954|accessdate=March 13, 2015}}\n*<sup>a</sup> \"Of all U.S. prep schools, few, if any, can beat the standards Hotchkiss has set. \u2014 \u00b6 2</ref>\n\n===International relations and diversity===\nMaria Hotchkiss was uninterested in establishing \"a school for the pampered sons of rich gentlemen.\" The school has enrolled international students since 1896.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jose A. Camprubi, Newspaper Owner |url= |newspaper=New York Times |location=New York |date=March 13, 1942 |page=19 |access-date= }}</ref>  In 1928, the school joined the [[English-Speaking Union]] and established the International Schoolboy Exchange. Established by the Class of 1948, the Fund for Global Understanding enables student participation in summer service projects across the world.<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/> In 1953, Hotchkiss alumnus [[John Van Voorhis#Personal life|Eugene Van Voorhis]] (g. 1951, Yale '55, Yale Law \u201858) incorporated the Ulysses S. Grant Foundation program to assist minority New Haven students with boarding school admission,<ref name=USGrantFoundation>{{cite web|url=http://archives.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/02_10/grant.html|title=A Firm Foundation: How does an ever-changing cast of undergraduates keep an educational program for New Haven schoolchildren going for 50 years? For the Ulysses S. Grant Foundation, the answer is adaptability.|first=Mark Alden|last=Branch|work=[[Yale Alumni Magazine]]|date=October 2002|accessdate=November 19, 2014|pages=2, 6|quote=But Eugene Van Voorhis '55, \u201858LLB remembers when things were different. When Van Voorhis came to Yale from Hotchkiss in 1951, reaching out to New Haven \"wasn't the 'shoe' thing to do,\" he recalls. Undaunted, Van Voorhis started a group to tutor middle school-aged African American students with an eye toward getting them admitted into elite boarding schools at a time when African American applicants were virtually unheard of in such places. Two years later, he incorporated his venture as the Ulysses S. Grant Foundation.\"... \"After two years of tutoring, the first \"graduate,\" Barry Loncke, was admitted to Hotchkiss. Four years later, he was admitted to Yale College in the Class of 1962; he is now a Superior Court judge in Sacramento, California.}}</ref> with Hotchkiss formally participating in addition to other recruitment initiatives from the 1960s onward,<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/> such as [[A Better Chance]] (ABC),<ref name=ABC>{{cite web|url=http://www.abetterchance.org/abetterchance.aspx?pgID=1256#Connecticut|title=Participating Schools: Independent Boarding Schools - Connecticut|publisher=A Better Chance Program|date=|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Greater Opportunity (GO) summer program for inner-city students,<ref name=GO>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-07-19/community/hc-hotchkiss-go-program-reunion-20130715_1_hotchkiss-school-hartford-public-high-school-alumni-relations|title=Reunion Held For Hotchkiss School's GO Program: Inner-City Kids Spent Summers At Private School|first=Chloe|last=Miller|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=July 19, 2013|accessdate=November 19, 2014|quote=The people that live up there would invite us on the weekends into their homes, to go to church with them and whatnot. There were a lot of families involved to take on all us inner-city kids, and the racial barrier was totally broken,\" Collins, who is black, said of the mostly white families who took the boys into their homes in Lakeville.}}</ref><ref name=GO-ED>{{cite web|url=http://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED026422.pdf|title=The Hartford-Hotchkiss Greater Opportunity Program: Interim Report to the State Department of Education and the Hartford Board of Education - Summer 1968|publisher=U.S. Department of Education's [[Institute of Education Sciences]]|date=Summer 1968|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> and Prep for Prep to foster minority leaders.<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/>\n\nThe school has a 43% diverse student body<ref name=WhoWeAre/> (21% international students),<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/> offers a School Year Abroad program,<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions/> and is a member of the Global Education Benchmark Group (GEBG),<ref name=GEBG/> [[Round Square (educational organisation)|Round Square]],<ref name=RoundSquare/> and [[Confucius Institute]] International Division (Hanban).<ref name=CIHanban>{{cite web|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_15883.htm|title=Confucius Classroom at Hotchkiss School|publisher=[[Confucius Institute]] International Division (Hanban)|date=November 1, 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, Hotchkiss partnered with [[Peking University High School]] to establish its study abroad, international division called [[Peking University High School#South Teaching Building (Dalton Academy)|Dalton Academy]].<ref name=Peking-Diplomat>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2010/08/beijings-study-abroad-market/|title=Beijing's Study Abroad Market: Beijing parents expect SAT cramming when selecting a high school. But what about the kids?|first=Jiang|last=Xueqin|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=August 11, 2010|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Peking-LitchfieldCountyTimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.countytimes.com/articles/2011/07/19/news/northwest_corner_journal/doc4e1f1b8db43a5387213146.txt|title=Chinese Students Learn About America at Portals|first=Kathryn|last=Boughton|publisher=Litchfield County Times|date=July 19, 2011|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty sexual misconduct===\nIn 2015, a male student sued the school, alleging that he had been raped and sexually harassed in \"an environment of well-known and tolerated sexual assaults, sexually violent hazing, and pedophilia\". In the suit, he said the Dormitory Master and instructor had drugged him and lured him to his quarters where he was raped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/Hotchkiss-School-Investigating-Sex-Abuse-Allegations-290976681.html|title=Former Hotchkiss School Student Raped by Teacher: Lawsuit|date=February 5, 2015|accessdate=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the lawsuit, he said he wrote an article for the student newspaper about the failure of the school to appropriately respond to complaints. The suit said the headmaster blocked publication and \"conspired to prevent (the plaintiff) from informing the students, parents and the school community about the faculty members's sexual assault and his aberrant and predatory propensities and behavior.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Exclusive-Hotchkiss-sued-for-alleged-sex-assaults-6064782.php|title=Exclusive Hotchkiss sued for alleged sex assaults|first=Daniel|last=Tepfer|date=Feb 6, 2015|website=Connecticut Post|accessdate=Aug 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of this complaint and others, the school hired a law firm to investigate. The law firm interviewed more than 150 people and reviewed more than 200,000 pages of documents.\n\nOn August 16, 2018, the firm released its report, which found that seven former faculty members had abused students for years, yet school administrators took no action, even when made aware of the [[sexual misconduct]]. The report said that the abuse, stretching from 1969 through 1992, involved at least 16 students and consisted of intercourse and unnecessary \"medical gynecological\" exams.\n\nA former headmaster who had been serving on the Board of Trustees resigned after cooperating with investigators. Board of Trustee representatives said the information would be turned over to law enforcement officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/hotchkiss-school-sexual-abuse_n_5b79b46ee4b018b93e94eb31|title=Connecticut Boarding School Says 7 Former Staffers Sexually Abused Students|date=Aug 19, 2018|website=HuffPost|accessdate=Aug 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nOperating on a semester schedule, Hotchkiss offers a [[classical education movement|classical education]],<ref name=WhoWeAreTraditions /> 224 courses, 7 foreign languages (Chinese, French, German, Greek, Latin, Russian and Spanish),<ref name=WhoWeAre /> and study abroad programs.<ref name=Intl>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotchkiss.org/abouthotchkiss/international-programs/index.aspx|title=About Hotchkiss: International Programs|publisher=The Hotchkiss School|accessdate=November 19, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129051945/http://www.hotchkiss.org/abouthotchkiss/international-programs/index.aspx|archivedate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> In 1991, the ''[[New York Times]]'' recognized Hotchkiss' summer program as, \"Summer School for the Very Ambitious\"<ref name=NYT-1991>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/15/nyregion/summer-school-for-the-very-ambitious.html|title=Summer School for the Very Ambitious|first=George|last=Judson|work=New York Times |date=August 15, 1991|accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref> and in 2011, as a private school leader in the [[farm-to-table]] movement,<ref name=NYT-2011>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/20/nyregion/prep-schools-encourage-students-to-learn-to-farm.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=At Prep School, Rolling Up Sleeves and Working the Soil|first=Wendy|last=Carlson|work=New York Times|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref> by incorporating agriculture into the curriculum since 2008.<ref name=Farm-NAIS>{{cite web|url=http://inspirationlab.org/story/4023|title=Hotchkiss's Fairfield Farm Grows Up|first=|last=|publisher=National Association of Independent Schools|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref> The year prior, the ''[[Deerfield Academy|Deerfield]] Scroll'' featured that \"many consider The Hotchkiss School to be the leader in environmental awareness among the top prep schools in the country.\"<ref name=DeerfieldScroll-2010>{{cite web|url=http://deerfield.edu/scroll/2010/01/are-they-greener-on-the-other-side-part-three-the-hotchkiss-school/|title=Are They Greener on the Other Side? Part Three: The Hotchkiss School|first=Sarah|last=Woolf|work=[[Deerfield Academy|Deerfield]] Scroll|date=January 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402201314/http://deerfield.edu/scroll/2010/01/are-they-greener-on-the-other-side-part-three-the-hotchkiss-school/|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe school has a 100% college matriculation rate,<ref name=WhoWeAre /> and among the classes of 2011\u201314, 33 enrolled at Yale, 19 at Harvard, and 16 at Princeton.<ref name=CollegeMatriculation>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotchkiss.org/academics/college-advising/matriculation-list/index.aspx|title=Academics: College Advising \u2013 Matriculation List (Classes of 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014)|publisher=The Hotchkiss School|accessdate=November 19, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120052943/http://www.hotchkiss.org/academics/college-advising/matriculation-list/index.aspx|archivedate=November 20, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' listed Hotchkiss as among the schools with a higher success rate (than Choate and Deerfield) in matriculation at Harvard, Princeton and six others (excluding Yale).<ref name=WSJ-2007>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/info-COLLEGE0711-sort.html|title=How the Schools Stack Up|first=Ellen|last=Gamerman |work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=December 28, 2007|accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurriculars==\n\n===Athletics===\nHotchkiss fields 19 interscholastic sports teams<ref name=WhoWeAre /> that compete in the [[Founders League]],<ref name=FoundersLeague /> [[Eight Schools Association#Athletics|Eight Schools Athletic Council]],<ref name=EightSchoolsAssociation /> [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC),<ref name=NEASC /> and [[Interscholastic Sailing Association]]'s New England Schools Sailing Association (NESSA) district.<ref name=ISA-NESSA-TrophyCase>{{cite web|url=http://nessa.hssailing.org/trophy-case|title=Trophy Case: District Championships|publisher=[[Interscholastic Sailing Association]]|date=|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Its colors are [[Yale Blue]] and white, with the mascot being the bearcat.<ref name=Athletics />\n\nIn 1933, [[Samuel Gottscho]] photographed the Hotchkiss baseball team, which appears in the [[Library of Congress]]' Gottscho-Schleisner Collection.<ref name=LOC-baseball>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/gsc1994028627/PP/|title=Schools. Hotchkiss School, baseball|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|date=May 4, 1933|accessdate=March 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:80%\"\n|-\n! style=\"